<HEAD>Ex-President Gets Six-Year Jail Term for Trying to Replace Prime
Minister</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT VILA, Vanuatu (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ex-President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Sokomanu </PERSON> was sentenced Tuesday to six years in jail after being convicted of trying to install his nephew as prime minister of this <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> island chain. <PERSON> Sokomanu </PERSON>, who has been president since 1980, was dismissed from office in January for plotting against Prime Minister <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Lini </PERSON>. <PERSON> Sokomanu </PERSON>'s nephew, <PERSON> Barak </PERSON> <PERSON> Sope </PERSON>, and opposition leader <PERSON> Maxime </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlot </PERSON> were given five-year prison sentences and former member of Parliament <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> was sentenced to two years. The charges against <PERSON> Sokomanu </PERSON>, <PERSON> Sope </PERSON> and <PERSON> Carlot </PERSON> carried maximum sentences of life imprisonment. Three defendants were acquitted. <PERSON> Sokomanu </PERSON> was convicted of inciting mutiny within <LOCATION> Vanuatu </LOCATION>'s paramilitary forces last December in an attempt to replace <PERSON> Lini </PERSON>'s elected government with an interim administration headed by Sokomanu and the other defendants were taken into police custody just before Christmas. At the time of of his arrest <PERSON> Sokomanu </PERSON> acknowledged his action was unconstitutional, but he said <PERSON> Lini </PERSON> was unable to govern after suffering a stroke. He said he tried to install <PERSON> Sope </PERSON> as prime minister to restore economic power. <PERSON> Sope </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lini </PERSON> had been engaged in a power struggle for more than a year. Acquitted by British-born Judge <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> were former member of Parliament <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Naupa </PERSON>, <PERSON> Sokomanu </PERSON>'s private secretary <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kalititi </PERSON> and <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Spooner </PERSON>. Those three and <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> had been charged with lesser counts of conspiracy to overthrow the government and with administering and making unlawful oaths and statements at a Dec. 18 swearing-in ceremony. <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> was brought in from the <LOCATION> Solomon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> to hear the most controversial case in <LOCATION> Vanuatu </LOCATION>'s brief history and to pass judgment. His decisions are subject to appeal. <PERSON> Sokomanu </PERSON> was removed from office in January by the <ORGANIZATION> Electoral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> which accused him of gross misconduct. <PERSON> Sokomanu </PERSON> had served as head of state and <PERSON> Lini </PERSON> as head of government since <LOCATION> Vanuatu </LOCATION> became independent in July 1980. <LOCATION> Vanuatu </LOCATION>, formerly the Anglo-French <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hebrides </LOCATION>, had been jointly administered by <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> since 1906. It has a population of about 130,000 and is 1,395 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>.
