<HEAD>U.S.-Soviet Women Surveyed About Family Life</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Seventy-nine percent of Soviet women and 43 percent of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> women think alcoholism is a chief cause of divorce, a poll shows. Poor communication wrecks most marriages, 77 of the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> women said in the survey. They ranked alcoholism second, while 39 percent of <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> women ranked parental interference second. The survey, based on an unscientific sampling, was conducted by Woman's Day, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> magazine geared toward suburban women, and <PERSON> Krestyanka </PERSON>, a Soviet magazine whose name translates as, `` Peasant Woman,'' although 54 percent of its respondents identified themselves as white-collar. `` This survey reveals there's nothing foreign about domestic difficulties,'' said <PERSON> Ellen </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Levine </PERSON>, Woman's Day editor in chief. `` Soviet and <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> women have more in common than they may have thought: too much work, troubled marriages, husbands who wo n't help, and alcoholism. `` Stress is the great equalizer,'' said <PERSON> Ethel </PERSON> <PERSON> Klein </PERSON>, associate professor of political science at <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, who interpreted the poll for Woman's Day. `` Women have hit a strong stress point in both societies.'' Fifty-six percent of the Soviet women surveyed said an ideal husband should be faithful and a good head of the family. More than 63 percent of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> women mentioned `` communicative,'' `` emotionally supportive'' and `` faithful'' as the virtues of the ideal husband. Only 2 percent of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> women thought good homemaking skills make an ideal husband. Still, 61 percent said <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> men must assume more responsibility for housework and 50 percent wanted men to help more with child care. Twenty percent of the Soviet women said men should do more at home and 13 percent said men should spend more time raising their kids. The surveys were conducted by mail so that rural <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> women without phones could be included. Women's Day received about 30,000 responses from women with a median age of 41; more than three-quarters are married and almost 90 percent have children. <PERSON> Krestyanka </PERSON> got back about 200,000 responses, with a median age of 30, three-fourths married and 78 percent with children. The <PERSON> Yankelovich </PERSON> <PERSON> Clancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Shulman </PERSON> polling firm tabulated the Woman's Day results
