<HEAD>Julia Child Recipe Set to Music</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Attention, dieters. The musical recipe for a wickedly delicious chocolate cake by <PERSON> Julia </PERSON> <PERSON> Child </PERSON> is being cooked up at the Kennedy Center tonight. It takes about 20 minutes to devour, and it does n't contain a single calorie. But composer <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoiby </PERSON> warns that his `` Bon Appetit!'' a new musical monologue performed by actress <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Stapleton </PERSON> with <PERSON> Hoiby </PERSON> at the piano, may tempt chocolate lovers to break their vows of abstinence. `` I am tempted not only by the lyrics but by the cake itself,'' confesses <PERSON> Hoiby </PERSON>, who is trying to observe a diet of such macrobiotic foods as cabbage, brown rice and fish with seaweed. `` I often give in to temptation and say I'll make up for it later,'' he said during a prerehearsal interview. `` I love chocolate cake. The things that are out of reach are what we love in this world.'' <PERSON> Hoiby </PERSON>'s piece is based on the videotape of a 1961 television cooking lesson by <PERSON> Julia </PERSON> <PERSON> Child </PERSON>, and will be served as the dessert course for an evening of <PERSON> Hoiby </PERSON>'s music at the Terrace Theater. After its world premiere here, <PERSON> Hoiby </PERSON> and <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Stapleton </PERSON> will perform the work at <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, on March 31 and at <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.M. </LOCATION>, on April 9. On stage, <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Stapleton </PERSON> sings and pantomimes her way around an imaginary kitchen, using lyrics taken from Miss Child's tape, as she prepares a `` very special, ve-e-ery choc ` late-ly, bittersweet, loooovely cake'' called <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Gateau </PERSON> au Chocolat, l ` Eminence `` What I love is her wonderful sense of theater,'' the actress says. `` She's not just a cook. She's a character, very rich and very humorous.'' Miss <PERSON> Stapleton </PERSON> makes the most of the TV chef's comic touches, tapping an invisible cake pan and instructing her audience to `` knock out the flour on the floor, if you have a self-cleaning kitchen like mine.'' And she engages in a fast-paced musical race with an electric mixer, as she beats egg whites in an unlined copper bowl. `` We're going to see who wins,'' she sings, `` and I think maybe I'll win ... because I'm bigger. <PERSON> Hoiby </PERSON> says `` Bon Appetit!'' _ which takes its title from Miss Child's familiar closing line _ was composed as a concert curtain-raiser for a longer work he wrote in 1984, his operatic version of the late <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> <PERSON> Draper </PERSON>'s monologue, `` The Italian Lesson.'' <PERSON> Hoiby </PERSON> and associate <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Shulgasser </PERSON> came up with the idea of using the script of a Julia Child cooking lesson as a vehicle for Miss <PERSON> Stapleton </PERSON>, a veteran of Broadway musicals who is better known as <PERSON> Archie </PERSON> <PERSON> Bunker </PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON> Edith </PERSON>, on the `` All in the Family'' TV series. Miss <PERSON> Stapleton </PERSON> wrote Miss Child for permission. Miss Child happily agreed, and sent a batch of her tapes for viewing. <PERSON> Hoiby </PERSON>, who watched them for four full days, became intrigued by the chef's `` rhapsodic phrases'' and musical metaphors `` Her speaking patterns really grab you, the phraseology, the unexpected little interjections,'' he said. `` There is a kind of musical cadence in her speech which one is n't aware of unless one starts to set it to music, and then there it is.'' Is there something musical, too, about chocolate cake? `` Well, you see, chocolate cake, it's a very special moment,'' <PERSON> Hoiby </PERSON> replied. `` It's an indulgence, something you do n't want to do too much of. It's like a reward _ you ate all your spinach, now you can have your reward. It's put in a very special category as a treat.'' Getting hungry? After tonight's concert, members of the audience will gather at a reception to nibble on the real thing, <LOCATION> Le </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gateau </LOCATION> au Chocolat, l'Eminence <PERSON> Brune </PERSON>, prepared from Miss Child's recipe by the <ORGANIZATION> Kennedy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> chef. `` The cake is going to be the icing,'' says <PERSON> Shulgasser </PERSON>.
