<HEAD>Court: Divorced Mother Can't Let Boyfriend Stay Over While Kids Are
Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIMBERLY M. SHEARIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The boyfriend of a mother of three can not spend the night while the children are home, the state's highest court has ruled. The state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday upheld a lower court decision to bar the boyfriend, <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> DiPippo </PERSON>, from staying overnight, saying the ruling raised no major constitutional issues. Civil libertarians expressed surprise at the decision and found the remark that the case raised no constitutional questions disturbing. `` I think that the state of <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> has made a very poor statemeent about women, divorced women, single parents and their children, and their collective rights to privacy in their own homes,'' said <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurst </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> attorney for <PERSON> Carla </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Parrillo </PERSON>. Ms. <PERSON> Parrillo </PERSON> and her husband, <PERSON> Justin </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, were divorced in May 1986, and Ms. <PERSON> Parrillo </PERSON> was given custody of her children, two daughters and a son, ages 8 13 at the time. <PERSON> Parrillo </PERSON> was given visitation rights. In June, the <PERSON> Parrillos </PERSON> returned to <ORGANIZATION> Family </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, and Ms. <PERSON> Parrillo </PERSON> wanted her ex-husband to see the children in a location away from her home. <PERSON> Parrillo </PERSON> wanted his ex-wife restrained from having any `` unrelated males'' stay overnight at her house. Ms. <PERSON> Parrillo </PERSON> contended that her ex-husband began to harass her upon learning that she was dating DiPippo. DiPippo stayed overnight once or twice a week, Ms. <PERSON> Parrillo </PERSON> said, and it caused no harm to her children, who were in separate bedrooms. She told the court that her children liked <PERSON> DiPippo </PERSON>, but she had no plans to marry him in the near future. <PERSON> Parrillo </PERSON> began reducing his support payments when he learned <PERSON> DiPippo </PERSON> was visiting, the high court said. The children told the lower court's judge in a private meeting that they all got along well with <PERSON> DiPippo </PERSON>, although the son said there were times he disliked the man. But the judge ruled the overnight visits `` in the presence of the children, were not conducive to their general well-being, at least in terms of their psychological welfare,'' the high court said. The judge also had noted that if Ms. <PERSON> Parrillo </PERSON> married DiPippo, the issue would become moot. Ms. <PERSON> Parrillo </PERSON> appealed, saying the judge erred because no evidence existed that her sleeping with DiPippo psychologically harmed her children. But the high court upheld the <ORGANIZATION> Family </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision, saying that ruling `` was without question directed at <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON>. ... <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> may still visit the marital domicile overnight, with the exception of those times when the children are with their mother.'' <PERSON> Hurst </PERSON> said she hoped Ms. <PERSON> Parrillo </PERSON> would appeal the decision. `` The practical effect on <PERSON> Carla </PERSON> <PERSON> Parrillo </PERSON> is that she is precluded from conducting her private activities in the privacy of her own home at her discretion,'' she said.
