<HEAD>Navy Recruit's Death Blamed on Safety Neglect</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The death of a 19-year-old <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> recruit during training a year ago resulted from the service's neglect for safety procedures and pressure on the training system from higher-ups, according to a congressional investigation. In a report released Tuesday, the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Mirecki </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Appleton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, died at the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Pensacola </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Rescue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Swimmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in part because of `` an intimidating, non-volunteer atmosphere and inadequate controls at the school and its superior commands.'' Some of the flaws remain uncorrected, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said. And it found that of 16 other <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> training deaths between Jan. 1, 1986, and the end of last year, safety problems contributed to five of the fatalities. `` The bottom line is that <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> instructors still are not trained to conduct high-risk training and that students still are not screened to make sure they can handle the dangers,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Toby </PERSON> <PERSON> Roth </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Wis </LOCATION>., who requested the investigation along with the other members of the state's congressional delegation <PERSON> Roth </PERSON> called <PERSON> Mirecki </PERSON>'s death `` a tragedy waiting to happen,'' pointing to <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> findings that he was unqualified for the swimming rescue course, had untrained and unsupervised instructors and was prevented from dropping out because of pressure on the school to increase the number of graduates it turned out. `` This <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> report is a catalog of failures by the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, which led to <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Mirecki </PERSON>'s death and others,'' <PERSON> Roth </PERSON> said at a news conference. He vowed to follow up to see that remaining problems are resolved and asked Vice Admiral <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Disher </PERSON>, head of the service's training system, to contact families of recruits who died in training `` to tell them what really happened.'' The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said it had discussed its findings with the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> and reported that officials `` generally agreed'' and `` were receptive to suggestions on how to improve training safety'' and accident investigations. <PERSON> Mirecki </PERSON> panicked during a swimming-pool drill known as `` sharks and daisies,'' in which swimmers must free themselves from an instructor who grabs them from behind, simulating a drowning person. After counseling and medical examination, he was found `` not physically qualified'' for the course because of a phobia of being held under water. But despite the findings, he was re-enrolled in the class and forced to undergo the drill again. <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Mirecki </PERSON> left the pool and clutched an equipment rack, shouting such things as `` I quit'' and `` Please do n't put me back in the water,'' but was dragged back to the pool by instructors. After a struggle in the pool, he was removed unconscious and could not be revived. An autopsy found that <PERSON> Mirecki </PERSON> probably died of heartbeat irregularity caused by extreme fear, fatigue and decreased oxygen. The lead instructor was found guilty by a general court martial of negligent homicide and sentenced to a demotion and 90 days' confinement Eight others associated with the class were given various administrative punishments, including demotions and reprimands. Some improvements have been made, <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said. The `` sharks and daisies'' drill has been dropped, instructors are given better training and safety equipment is kept on hand at the swimming pool. There also is a clearer policy regarding students' rights to drop out of a course, the investigators said. But the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said there remains great pressure on students not to drop out of a course because it is made clear to them that doing so will adversely affect their careers, and that there still is no system to alert instructors to students with a history of problems.
