<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> did not go into loving detail on what <PERSON> Raisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> wore or who did her hair, but it did report on what the first lady was thinking about some world and domestic issues _ an unusual turn for Soviet media. Mrs. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, wife of the president and <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief, <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, spoke at a a reception she gave Monday in honor of International Women's Day, a Soviet holiday that is being celebrated today. She talked about her husband's reform policies and about how the world's women have improved prospects for peace, and <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>, the official Soviet news agency, reported her views. State-run television frequently shows the stylish <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> first lady and Western journalists interview her. But it is rare for fellow Soviets to be let in on her thoughts. `` If people currently are more confident of a peaceful future, we know that much of the credit goes to women actively working on all continents for friendship, cooperation and profound mutual understanding of nations,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said at the reception, as reported by <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>. For <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> to be covering the reception itself _ for wives of ambassadors and other diplomats in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, wives of members of the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Politburo </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> women in various fields _ was unusual. Before <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> came to power four years ago, <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> wives almost invariably were kept backstage. Mrs. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> changed that. The attractive, 57-year-old former teacher of Marxist-Leninist philosophy has taken a role somewhat resembling that of the wife of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> president. Not all Soviets are delighted with the change. Many are taken aback by her wardrobe, large and glamorous by Soviet standards. Others grumble that she is too involved in her husband's work. On Monday, Mrs. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> gave the grumblers some ammunition by going public with some of her views. Speaking of her husband's reforms, she said, `` Soviet people are putting into practice plans of revolutionary restructuring. We are connecting to it the destiny of our country, of our nation. We want our public life in all aspects _ socio-economic, political, moral, ecological, and in the sphere of human rights and freedoms _ to be worthy of a human being. `` By transforming and renewing our society on a socialist basis, on the principles of humanism and democracy, we are making our country more open for all the nations of the world.' She greeted her guests individually and gave each a bouquet, reported <PERSON> Rebecca </PERSON> <PERSON> Matlock </PERSON>, wife of <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Matlock </PERSON>. `` She's a very attractive, intelligent and vocal woman. If they let her speak more often, everyone would benefit,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Matlock </PERSON> told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. The Gorbachevs later attended a televised celebration held in the <LOCATION> Bolshoi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Theater </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> to mark International Women's Day. This time, things were a little more typical. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> sat on the dais with other Politburo members and dignitaries. His wife was in the audience.
