<HEAD>Whistleblower Bill on the Move Again in the Senate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A bill to protect so-called `` whistleblowers'' who expose government waste, fraud and abuse is back in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> after a compromise between sponsors and the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration. `` This very well might be the first bill to be signed by the president this year,'' Sen. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Grassley </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Iowa </LOCATION>, said at a news conference Tuesday in which sponsors unveiled a revised version of the measure. The bill would ease the way for federal employees to win reinstatement if demoted or fired after disclosing mismanagement. Then-President <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> blocked the measure by a pocket veto, meaning he refused to sign the bill and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> was out of session at the time. He said it could result in the government fighting legal battles against itself. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s move received heavy criticism in a surprised <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and from Democratic presidential nominee <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. Lawmakers agreed under the compromise to give up a provision of last year's bill that would have allowed a special counsel representing employees to go to court, said Sen. <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>, D-Mich. In turn, the administration agreed to a provision barring the special counsel from opposing whistleblowers in any action before the <ORGANIZATION> Merit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, the agency that enforces civil service safeguards. The administration also agreed to greater privacy protection under the bill, while the senators approved a minor rewording under which employees are deemed whistleblowers if their exposure of waste, fraud or abuse was `` a contributing factor'' in the decision to discipline them. The change inserted the word `` contributing.'' Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> promised in a letter to <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> `` our cooperation to discourage any amendments, in either body of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, that might in any way interfere with this agreement.'' `` None of the changes to which we have agreed detracts in any way from the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' intent to strengthen whistleblower protections,'' the letter said.
