<HEAD>Administration Promises to Spare Landsat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Landsat earth-sensing satellites appear to be getting a reprieve, with an administration pledge to keep them running and a variety of federal agencies being asked to foot the bill. The two satellites had been threatened with a shutdown when funds ran out on March 31. But <PERSON> Thonas </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pyke </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atmospheric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> reported that while details remain to be worked out, the administration is committed to keep the satellite system running. A shutdown would have amounted to `` turning off the lights, closing the door and retiring from the field,'' of remote sensing, said Rep. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Scheuer </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on natural resources. The federal agencies that make the most use of the satellite data are being asked to contribute to keep the system operating after March 31, <PERSON> Pyke </PERSON> told the subcommittee. It will cost about $ 9.4 million to keep the system running for the rest of the fiscal year. <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roe </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>, told the subcommittee that he has a meeting scheduled with Vice President <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> to discuss details of the funding. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> has been coordinating the new Landsat funding as head of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. `` We've got to stop this damned nonsense,'' <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> said of the Landsat funding problem. Funding was a continuing battle under the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, which initiated the transfer of the system to private hands. That transfer, to the <ORGANIZATION> Earth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Observation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Satellite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>, is incomplete. Federal money is still used in operating the satellites, which measure land use, water flow, vegetation and mineral locations and provide detailed mapping information. The two satellites are currently beyond their original design lifetimes. A replacement, Landsat 6, is n't scheduled for launch until 1991. In the meantime, <ORGANIZATION> Landsats </ORGANIZATION> 4 and 5 continue to supply useful data. If they are turned off for lack of funds the only source for similar information would be the French SPOT-Image satellite system or the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Pyke </PERSON> told the subcommittee that the EOSAT company, the private firm handling the Landsat data, has been asked to contribute part of the funding to keep the satellites running, but no commitment has been received. Federal agencies that seem likely sources of funds, he said, include the <ORGANIZATION> Departments </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION>, Agriculture and Interior and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. Rep. <PERSON> Lamar </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Texas </LOCATION>, urged that the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> be asked for assistance as well. `` It's an absolute shame that we've come to this juncture,'' concluded Rep. <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> McCurdy </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Okla </LOCATION>. He termed threatening to shut down the satellites a `` pretty expensive game of chicken.''
