<HEAD>Guerrilla Leader Says Backing from ASEAN Weakening</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> resistance's main backer, the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southeast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Asian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, has lessened its once firm support for a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> peacekeeping force in postwar <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> and for other key resistance proposals, a guerrilla leader says. Prince <PERSON> Norodom </PERSON> <PERSON> Ranariddh </PERSON> also said Tuesday that he would leave for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> this weekend to ask <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for more covert aid to force <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> to be more flexible at the negotiating table. The resistance has repeatedly requested arms, but <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> provides only limited non-lethal aid. <PERSON> Ranariddh </PERSON> is the son of central Cambodian resistance leader Prince <PERSON> Norodom </PERSON> <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> and commands one of three guerrilla groups resisting <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s 10-year-old occupation of <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. He told a group of reporters that <ORGANIZATION> ASEAN </ORGANIZATION>'s support for the resistance proposals weakened at peace talks last month in <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> ASEAN </ORGANIZATION> mediated those talks, which brought together <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> and the warring factions in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ranariddh </PERSON> said he was troubled by the shift. He said only a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> peacekeeping force can prevent renewed fighting and a return of Vietnamese troops, who have said they hope to withdraw next year, or by brutal <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> and the government it installed in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> have opposed introducing an armed international force. `` I am very sorry for the sake of my people that the <ORGANIZATION> ASEAN </ORGANIZATION> stand is not as firm as before,'' <PERSON> Ranariddh </PERSON> told a group of reporters. He said a majority of <ORGANIZATION> ASEAN </ORGANIZATION> delegates at the conference did not support an international peackeeping force and no longer clearly support the idea of an interim postwar government under <PERSON> Prince </PERSON> <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON>'s leadership and comprised of the three resistance factions and the Vietnam-backed regime. `` They do not support even the idea of having free self-determination and free elections in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>,'' he said. In 1982, <ORGANIZATION> ASEAN </ORGANIZATION> sponsored the formation of the guerrilla coalition. It gives the group sanctuary and arms and leads the diplomatic struggle against <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. The non-Communist <ORGANIZATION> ASEAN </ORGANIZATION> includes <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brunei </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. The guerrilla coalition joins the nationalist forces of <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> and <PERSON> Son </PERSON> <PERSON> Sann </PERSON> with a group they strongly distrust, the militarily potent <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>. The fanatical Communist group killed hundreds of thousands of people when it ruled <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> from 1975 until <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> ousted it in the late 1978 invasion. <PERSON> Ranariddh </PERSON> would not name the <ORGANIZATION> ASEAN </ORGANIZATION> countries whose support had weakened, nor say why that support had weakened. He said, however, that said a notable exception was <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>'s Prime Minister <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuan </PERSON> <PERSON> Yew </PERSON>. In January, <LOCATION> Thai </LOCATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Chatichai </PERSON> <PERSON> Choonhavan </PERSON> was host to an unprecedented visit to <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> by <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON>, premier of <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>'s Vietnamese-installed government Some diplomats said <PERSON> Chatichai </PERSON> has seriously weakened the resistance in his rush to get a settlement and transform <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>'s battlefields into markets for Thai goods <PERSON> Ranariddh </PERSON> has said his father, who had quit as resistance coalition president, resumed the post in February to counter the increasing worldwide support for Hun Sen. <PERSON> Ranariddh </PERSON> said that during his trip to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> he would tell officials that other steps are needed to weaken the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> aside from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attempts to pressure <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> to halt its aid to them. He expressed optimism that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, which arms the guerrillas, and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, which arms <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, will reach an agreement on <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> during their summit in May. He said they recently had converged on many points and all that remains was for the Soviets to guarantee a Vietnamese pullout and the Chinese to guarantee in turn that the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> will not return to power. `` If they will overcome this, -LRB- the settlement is -RRB- finished,'' <PERSON> Ranariddh </PERSON> said.
