<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government says it has concluded what most Poles have long accepted as fact: that Soviet forces, not Nazi troops, systematically massacred more than 4,000 interned Polish army officers during World War II. The statement on Tuesday represented Communist authorities' first official rejection of the longtime Soviet line on the <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> massacre _ perhaps the most sensitive and emotional issue in Soviet-Polish relations. `` We think that everything indicates that the crime was committed by the Stalinist NKVD,'' the <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION>'s predecessor, government spokesman <PERSON> Jerzy </PERSON> <PERSON> Urban </PERSON> said during his weekly news conference. The Polish government also pressed the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> to speed its review of the incident. The official Soviet news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> did not report the development. The announcement comes at a crucial moment in monthlong talks between the government and opposition on restoring the legal status of the Solidarity free trade union movement and ending an acute economic crisis. The slain officers were among 15,000 Polish reserve officers rounded up by the invading Soviets in 1939 and Nazi troops uncovered their bodies in 1943 from common graves in the <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> forest near the Soviet city of <LOCATION> Smolensk </LOCATION>. Each had been killed by a single bullet to the back of the head. Official Soviet and Polish histories have long held that the officers were killed by the <PERSON> Nazis </PERSON>, who broke a non-aggression pact and invaded the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in 1941, but Western historians blamed the Soviets. No trace was found of the other nearly 11,000 reserve officers and many Poles consider their disappearance and the <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> massacre a deliberate effort by <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> to eliminate the cream of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s intelligensia For them, the very legitimacy of the ruling Communists in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> is undermined by the ruthless methods <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> employed in seeing to it that they came to power after the war. <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> formed a joint commission in 1987 to consider the evidence on <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> and other so-called `` blank spots'' in Polish-Soviet history. The Polish side has submitted its material and indications have emerged of growing impatience with the Soviet review. Last month, an official newspaper published a story on a wartime <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> report that concludes what Western historians have long held _ that the officers murdered at <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> were killed by the Soviets in 1940. Urban has previously said the inscription on a monument in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> blaming the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> for <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> will be changed. On Tuesday, he said Soviet historians were analyzing historial material on the massacre `` and are right to state that it's only circumstantial evidence.'' But he said <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> wants the Soviets to speed up their review of the material. `` The difficult process of erasing blank spots in <LOCATION> Polish-Soviet </LOCATION> relations'' should serve to strengthen friendship between the two countries and to support `` Soviet perestroika instead of damaging it,'' Urban added. <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> was attacked first by the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> from the <LOCATION> west </LOCATION> and then from the east by the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in September 1939.
