<HEAD>`Run for Your Wife!,' A British Farce, Opens on Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS three grafs with other reviews; No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 `` Run for Your Wife!'' gives <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> theatergoers a chance to see an authentic production of a British sex farce without having to cross the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION>. Whether they would want to is another question entirely. The play, which opened Tuesday at Broadway's <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> Theater, is full of leers, lunges and lame sex jokes. It could bring back celibacy. `` Run for Your Wife!'' stars <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooney </PERSON>, who also wrote and directed. He strikes out on all three counts. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> End </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Cooney </PERSON> is sort of a one-man play industry. His other successful efforts there include such supposedly spicy concoctions as `` Not Now, Darling,'' `` Move Over, Mrs. <PERSON> Markham </PERSON>,'' `` Why Not Stay for Breakfast?'' and `` Two Into One.'' The titles are better than the plays. The plot of `` Run for Your Wife!'' spins out of control early. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, played by <PERSON> Cooney </PERSON>, is a <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> taxi cab driver. He has one wife, <PERSON> Mary </PERSON>, in <LOCATION> Wimbledon </LOCATION>, and another, <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON>, in <LOCATION> Streatham </LOCATION>. Both of their tacky apartments, by set supervisor <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Anania </PERSON>, are on stage simultaneously. You can tell them apart because one is blue, the other yellow. His wives are color-coded to match the apartments. One wears blue, the other yellow. That's the extent of their characterizations. When <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> saves a little old lady from a mugging and gets beaten up, his twin living arrangements unravel. Most of the evening is spent trying to prevent one wife from finding out about the other. With one glorious exception, the acting is cardboard _ flat and gray. Only <PERSON> Paxton </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitehead </PERSON>, as a well-meaning but bumbling neighbor, manages to rise above the drivel. He actually seems to believe what he is saying. That's no small accomplishment considering <PERSON> Cooney </PERSON>'s inane dialogue. The second act trades boring for offensive. It bashes homosexuals with some crude jokes, primarily focused on one limp-wristed character who wears a lavender jumpsuit in case you ca n't figure out his sexual preference. The play has none of the style or wit of `` Lend Me a Tenor,'' another farce which arrived last week. In fact, it makes that harmless trifle seem like <PERSON> Noel </PERSON> <PERSON> Coward </PERSON>. `` ` Run for Your Wife!'' is one of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s biggest hits. It has clocked more than 2,500 performances and shows no sign of slowing down. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, it should expire quickly. In other reviews, <PERSON> Mel </PERSON> <PERSON> Gussow </PERSON> wrote in The <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Times: `` Accepting the ground rules for allowable contrivances in farce, the play is still burdened with blind alleys, limp jokes, forced puns and troubled entendres.'' `` ` Run For Your Wife' is what is known in the trade as an Audience Show,'' wrote <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kissel </PERSON> in the <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>. `` What this means is that it is so witless and inane that no self-respecting critic can possibly endorse it, but audiences enjoy it tremendously.'' `` The premises of the joke are ramshackle, its convolutions arbitrary and its conclusion quite remarkably inconclusive,'' wrote <PERSON> Clive </PERSON> <PERSON> Barnes </PERSON> in the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>. `` The results are shabby, with the actors busting a gut for laughs, rather like a TV sitcom going down for the third time without a script.''
