<SECOND>PM-AIDS Settlement,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyer: Award Sets Record For AIDS Suits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man who said he contracted AIDS from blood products during heart surgery in 1985 will collect the largest settlement for anyone who has contracted the deadly syndrome, his attorney said. Attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Habush </PERSON> said Monday that his client, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON>, avoided an appeals battle over a $ 3.9 million jury award because of the settlement. The amount was not disclosed, but <PERSON> Habush </PERSON> said it was `` very favorable and still very much a record in dollars in AIDS cases.'' The largest previous award is believed to be $ 1.6 millon for an <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> man who contracted AIDS from a blood product that promotes clotting. That verdict was later overturned on grounds the evidence was insufficient to prove negligence by the laboratory that provided the product. A <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> jury in December awarded $ 750,000 to the family of a 5-year-old who contracted the virus from blood he received during a heart operation in 1983. And in February a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> jury awarded <PERSON> Rock </PERSON> <PERSON> Hudson </PERSON>'s lover, <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Christian </PERSON>, $ 21.75 million because <ORGANIZATION> Hudson </ORGANIZATION> failed to tell him he had AIDS. The case increased the responsibility of AIDS sufferers to tell sexual companions of their plight. <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON> wanted his case resolved quickly so that he could decide how the money would be used, including what charities he would support, before he died. The 63-year-old man testified during the trial that he expected to live no more than one year. A <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> jury had awarded the suburban <LOCATION> Brookfield </LOCATION> man $ 3.9 million in damages in December, but attorneys said appeals could have taken years. The man had filed suit against the <ORGANIZATION> Blood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southeastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION>, which provided blood products used during his operation. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dawson </PERSON>, the blood center's lawyer, said the case was settled to both sides' satisfaction. `` The blood center remains confident that it was not negligent and that there was no liability in this case at all,'' he said. The plaintiff argued the center was negligent for distributing blood products that were n't tested for the AIDS virus even though it had tested products on hand. The blood center's attorneys said that, at the time, they could not be sure of the reliability of AIDS tests and were reluctant to replace untested blood with tested blood. The plaintiff received the blood April 23, 1985, six weeks after the blood center began testing blood for the AIDS virus. AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, breaks down the body's immune system and leaves the victim open to outbreaks of other diseases. No cure is known. It is spread through sexual contact, transfusions of blood and blood products, and the sharing of contamined hypodermic needles or syringes by drug abusers.
