<HEAD>Army Closes Proposed Settlement, Evicts Settlers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BET ARYE, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The army shut down an illegal Jewish settlement today, turning out a small group of Israelis who pitched a tent on the hilltop site in an attempt to launch a new community. The bid to create another Jewish enclave in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> followed a rally attended by 10,000 people in <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION> whose organizers called for the founding of eight such settlements. Elswhere in the occupied lands today, Palestinians staged a general strike to mark the 15-month anniversary of their uprising. Seven Arabs were shot and wounded during clashes with troops in the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, Arab hospital officials said. The army said it was checking the reports. Palestinian women staged pro-PLO demonstrations in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> town of <LOCATION> Beit </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jalla </LOCATION> and in <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> to mark International Women's Day The latest leaflet issued by underground leaders of the uprising against <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s 21-year occupation praised women for their `` heroic role ... in the liberation war.'' In east <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, police imposed a curfew on the Arab Isawiye section and rounded up men suspected of involvement in recent protests, police said. At least 15 Palestinians were arrested, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio said. After Tuesday night's rally in <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION>, a group of would-be settlers set out for the site of a proposed settlement called Ofarim. The site is about 15 miles east of <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION> on land occupied by <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> since it was captured from <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> in the 1967 <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> war. The government's coalition agreement calls for setting up eight settlements, but final approval has not been granted. The <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, controlled by the left-center <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, says the country can not afford the new settlements. Two army jeeps blocked the entrance to the Ofarim site this morning. A <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> official who demanded anonymity said eight activists from the right-wing <ORGANIZATION> Betar </ORGANIZATION> youth movement had set up a tent at the site during the night but later left at the order of soldiers. `` It was a symbolic takeover of the land. When the army came, they left voluntarily,'' said <PERSON> Yaakov </PERSON> <PERSON> Narodetsky </PERSON>, general secretary of <PERSON> Bet </PERSON> <PERSON> Aryeh </PERSON>, a settlement about one mile from the Ofarim site. Other hopeful settlers last night drove three large mobile homes out to another Jewish community, <LOCATION> Beit </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Horon </LOCATION>, and said they planned to move out to the proposed new settlement of <PERSON> Talmon </PERSON> later in the week. More than 70,000 Jewish settlers coexist uneasily with 1.7 million Palestinians in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, maintaining more than 130 settlements. Many are dedicated to continuing <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s control of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. Settlers have called for moving even more Jews out to the territories to strengthen <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s hold on the land. <PERSON> Elyakim </PERSON> <PERSON> Haetzni </PERSON>, an activist in the settlement movement, said on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s state-run radio station this morning that the settlers would oppose any peace settlement that called for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s withdrawal from the territories `` The state of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> can not turn Jews out of the state of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Haetzni </PERSON> said. Palestinians throughout the occupied territories began a general strike to mark the 15th month of the revolt that began Dec. 8, 1987. At least 391 Palestinians and 17 Israelis have been killed in the uprising.
