<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Refuseniks,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jewish Women Begin Hunger Strikes to Protest Emigration Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nearly 50 Jewish women across the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> began a three-day hunger strike today to protest what they say are arbitrary policies that bar their emigration, a participant said. It is the third year in a row that <ORGANIZATION> Jewish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Women </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Against </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Refusal </ORGANIZATION>, whose members have been denied exit visas, have held a hunger strike beginning on International Women's Day, a Soviet holiday celebrated on March 8. `` These three hunger strikes have all been during the years of perestroika. Everyone talks a lot about all the changes due to perestroika, but the situation in emigration is still the same,'' said hunger strike organizer <PERSON> Inna </PERSON> <PERSON> Ioffe </PERSON>, who first applied for an exit visa 10 years ago. Perestroika is what President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> calls his reform program. The women are protesting Soviet emigration procedures and calling on Soviet leaders to set up a judicial system to review their cases. About half of the 46 women participating in the hunger strike have been refused emigration for reasons of state secrecy, <PERSON> Ioffe </PERSON> said. Soviet authorities have told them they can not leave because they or their relatives have knowledge of state secrets, she said. The other half have been denied emigration because their parents or divorced spouses have failed to certify that they have no financial claims on the would-be emigrants, she said. Women in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kiev </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minsk </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vilnius </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Irkutsk </LOCATION> and other cities were participating in the hunger strike, <PERSON> Ioffe </PERSON> said. `` We have no laws to lean on, and we are never given reasonable reasons for the refusals,'' she said. <PERSON> Ioffe </PERSON> said she has been told she can not emigrate because her 76-year-old mother-in-law, who also wants to emigrate, was exposed to state secrets in her work as a botanist. More than 20,000 Soviet Jews were allowed permission to emigrate in 1988. <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> Semenovsky </PERSON>, who has sought in vain for three years to obtain a Soviet exit visa, said at a recent <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> demonstration of the so-called Jewish refuseniks that 80,000 others have had applications refused. The majority of the women who participated in the 1988 and 1987 hunger strikes have now emigrated, said <PERSON> Ioffe </PERSON>, who also took part in those hunger strikes.
