<HEAD>Izvestia Says Soviet AIDS Cases Rising Fast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 AIDS is spreading at an alarming rate in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, with the number of infected or ill people forecast to increase nearly tenfold next year, the government daily <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> says. The newspaper quoted the health minister, <PERSON> Yevgeny </PERSON> <PERSON> Chazov </PERSON>, as saying AIDS now poses no less a danger to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> than nuclear weapons. `` The alarming situation with AIDS demands rapid and decisive measures,'' <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday night in the latest of a series of reports in the Soviet press expressing growing concern about the deadly disease. The Soviets once claimed acquired immune deficiency syndrome was strictly a Western problem caused by decadent capitalist sexual mores and drug use. Homosexuals and intravenous drug users are two of the groups at greatest risk. Soviet papers once even claimed AIDS was the result of a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> experiment in biological warfare. Soviet scientists since have debunked such claims, saying their country needs to mobilize more resources to fight the spread of the disease, which saps the body's natural defenses and leaves it open to onslaught by other ailments. According to <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION>, however, the AIDS virus is spreading at an alarming rate among Soviets. In 1988, the paper said, 81 people in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> were carriers of the AIDS virus. By Feb. 1, it said, 44 more cases were known and now the total number of people infected with the virus is more than 140. `` It's expected that next year, there will be 1,342 sick people,'' <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> said, apparently referring to carriers of the virus, rather than people actually suffering symptoms. Of four Soviets actually suffering AIDS symptoms, three have died to date, <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> said. The government newspaper, reporting on a meeting of a special Soviet commission created to fight epidemics, quoted <PERSON> Chazov </PERSON> as saying warnings to the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> that AIDS could become a national calamity had been ignored. `` The threat that we face is no less than the ecological ` bomb' or nuclear weapons,'' <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> quoted <PERSON> Chazov </PERSON> as saying `` He also stated that workers of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S.S.R. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> on numerous occasions tried to inform the government that the situation was menacing. But noted scientists dealing with the problem eliminated the acuteness of the question, saying it was all a false alarm.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had 86,157 AIDS victims as of last month, according to the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>.
