<SECOND>PM-Templeton Prize, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0490,0725</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scot And German Named Co-Winners Of Top Religion Prize</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS to MacLeod throughout, CORRECTS to Mother Teresa sted
Theresa; Embargoed until at 11 a.m. EST, time set by source</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Rev. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> MacLeod </PERSON>, an innovative Scottish churchman, and West German physicist <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Freidrich </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Weizsaecker </PERSON> today were named winners of the 1989 <ORGANIZATION> Templeton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prize </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Progress </ORGANIZATION> in Religion. The prize, amounting this year to $ 435,000, is the world's biggest and is deliberately kept larger than Nobel prizes in the sciences and literature This is the first time in the award's 16 years that it has been divided between two winners, a result of rankings by an international panel of judges, a spokesman said. <PERSON> MacLeod </PERSON>, 92, of <LOCATION> Edinburgh </LOCATION>, was chosen for his founding of the famed <ORGANIZATION> Iona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>, an ecumenical center of prayer, peacemaking and work that has influenced church life in many countries. <PERSON> Weizsaecker </PERSON>, 76, of <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION>, was named for initiating dialogue between the disciplines of science and religion and for research into links between physics, cosmology and theology. <PERSON> MacLeod </PERSON> said in a statement he would use half of the money for direct action against hunger and the other half for work for peace. <PERSON> Weizsaecker </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> layman and the brother of West German President <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Weizsaecker </PERSON>, said his share would go to deepening relationships between science and faith. The winners were announced at a news conference at the <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> for the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> by <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Templeton </PERSON>, American investment counselor and financier, who founded the prize in 1972. He said its purpose is to encourage inter-religious understanding and to help `` people in all nations to grow spiritually in their love of God and understanding of God.'' Previous winners have included the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> nun <PERSON> Mother </PERSON> <PERSON> Teresa </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Calcutta </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> evangelist <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> and the Russian-expatriate writer <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Solzhenitsyn </PERSON>. <PERSON> Weizsaecker </PERSON> is the second scientist to win the prize. The Rev. <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaki </PERSON>, an astrophysicist at <ORGANIZATION> Seton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, won two years ago. Choice of last year's winner, <PERSON> Inamullah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, secretary-general of the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moslem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, was temporarily delayed after some Jewish leaders alleged he had links to anti-Semitism. But the award subsequently was made after an inquiry found the criticisms unjustified. The nine judges for the competition this year included former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Treasury Secretary <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, <PERSON> Roman </PERSON> <PERSON> Catholic </PERSON> <PERSON> Archishop </PERSON> <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> McGrath </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> Foreign Secretary Sir <PERSON> Geoffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Howe </PERSON>. <PERSON> MacLeod </PERSON>, a Church of <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> clergyman, left a wealthy parish to minister to shipbuilding workers and their families in <LOCATION> Glasgow </LOCATION>. In 1938, he founded the ecumenical community on the isle of <LOCATION> Iona </LOCATION> off <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>'s west coast. With its simple monastic-style commitment to a fivefold rule of daily prayer and Scripture study, tithing, peacemaking, and responsible work, the community has drawn interest of Christians around the world. About 100,000 visit there annually to experience its methods first-hand as a model for religious renewal, peace and <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> unity. <PERSON> MacLeod </PERSON>, who had become a pacifist after witnessing the slaughter of World War I as a military captain, also founded an early peace organization, the <ORGANIZATION> Fellowship </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reconciliation </ORGANIZATION>, which now has branches in most countries. He stepped down in 1967 as leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Iona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>, which has about 200 resident members and thousands of supporter elsewhere. Elevated to the British <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lords </ORGANIZATION>, he continues a broad schedule of teaching. <PERSON> Weizsaecker </PERSON> was cited as pioneering `` the development of the inter-relationships of physics, cosmology and theology'' and laying `` the groundwork for the renewal of faith.'' An astrophysicist, his research into cosmology led him after World War II to initiate conversations between scientists and theologians, originally in 1949 at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gottingen </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, and later elsewhere. Such conversations spread to other countries in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, resulting in an international conference in 1978 on science and faith sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Churches </ORGANIZATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Weizsaecker </PERSON>, who has written about 40 books on physics, astronomy, cosmology and religion, has taught at universities of <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Stasbourg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Gottingen </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hamburg </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION>. He recently retired as director of the <ORGANIZATION> Max </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Starnberg </LOCATION>, a position he held since 1970.
