<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-USLawyer     03-08 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-US Lawyer,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Says Spectators Can Take Notes in American's Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled today that spectators may take notes during most trials, and an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> lawyer who brought the case said the decision would help open the Japanese legal system to needed reform. Until today's ruling, only reporters for major newspapers and radio and television stations were allowed to take notes during most trials. The decision came in a case brought by <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Repeta </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> attorney denied permission to take notes at a tax trial in 1983-84. Although it ruled in his favor, the court said <PERSON> Repeta </PERSON>'s inability to take notes during the trial was not serious enough to warrant paying the $ 10,000 damages he demanded. While attending the tax trial as part of research for a book on Japanese law, <PERSON> Repeta </PERSON>, 38, was repeatedly refused permission to take notes. With support from the <ORGANIZATION> Japanese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, he lodged a complaint, which was rejected by <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. `` As of today, anyone can go into any courtroom in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and will be allowed to take notes,'' <PERSON> Repeta </PERSON> said today. `` In a democracy, people have to have free access to the courts, or they ca n't be satisfied that the criminal process is being used fairly.'' <PERSON> Repeta </PERSON> told reporters there were `` very serious violations of fundamental human rights principles'' in Japanese criminal trials, including the holding of suspects for long periods without bail and without access to a lawyer. In the tax case, <PERSON> Repeta </PERSON> observed, the defendant was held for 2 -LCB- years without bail. `` The best remedy for such problems is public knowledge of what goes on in the courtroom,'' he said. In a rare appearance by a foreigner before the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Repeta </PERSON> told the judges in a January hearing that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> now has a responsibility to set an international legal example. `` The world looks to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> to take a leadership role, not only in economics but also in the cultural and political fields,'' he said. About 30 Japanese supported Repeta in the case, including lawyers, reporters and writers. His Japanese lawyer, <PERSON> Yoichi </PERSON> <PERSON> Kitamura </PERSON>, said it took an American to bring the case `` because Japanese are accustomed to the fact that spectators are not allowed to take notes.'' In <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s controversial `` press club'' system, most government agencies maintain semi-official press clubs that generally exclude reporters from small newspapers and magazines, and foreign correspondents. Until today's ruling, only members of judiciary press clubs were allowed to take notes during most trials. Members of press clubs still do not have access to court documents.
