<HEAD>A Look at Chinese-Tibet Violence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tibetan resentment toward Chinese rule, largely muffled since a failed uprising in 1959, has erupted in violence four times since 1987 in the capital of <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION>. Here is a chronology of the incidents: Sept. 27, 1987 _ Police move in to arrest leaders of a small pro-independence march led by 21 <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> monks. Oct. 1, 1987 _ Chinese National Day. About 2,000 Tibetans, angered by the arrests, storm <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION>'s central Barkhor Square, setting fire to a police station, waving the banned <LOCATION> Tibetan </LOCATION> flag and stoning police. Chinese officials say six died and 19 were injured. Tibetans and foreign witnesses put the death toll at 14 and say hundreds were injured and arrested. March 5, 1988 _ Two days of violence begin on the final day of a major prayer festival, when a monk stands up during ceremonies at <LOCATION> Jokhang </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Temple </LOCATION> and begins shouting for independence. Rioters loot and burn shops and set fire to vehicles. Chinese officials say one policeman died when Tibetans stabbed him and pushed from a window and another 300 were injured. Unconfirmed reports from foreign travelers put the death toll at 24. Dec. 10, 1988 _ About 30 <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> monks and nuns, some carrying the Tibetan flag, march into the central square outside <ORGANIZATION> Jokhang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> to commemorate the 40th anniversary of the U.N. Declaration on Human Rights. Crowds surge toward the marchers and begin throwing stones at police, who open fire and kill at least one monk and a child. March 5, 1989 _ A small pro-independence demonstration by monks on the anniversary of the March 1988 riots touches off widespread violence, with hundreds of mostly young Tibetans rampaging through the streets, burning and destroying Chinese-owned buildings and property and stoning police. March 7, 1989 _ The government declares martial law in <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION> and puts the death toll from the latest violence at 12, including one policeman. Tibetans say police shot scores of people to death.
</TEXT>
