<BYLINE>5,000 Students March Legally in Warsaw; 3,000 Rally in Southern
Poland ^By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 5,000 young people marched peacefully today to mark the anniversary of 1968 police beatings of students and to celebrate a government promise to legalize a banned student group. About 3,000 students at <ORGANIZATION> Jagiellonian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in the southern city of <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION> also rallied to support the group, the <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Students </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. Those students, heeding an appeal from the university rector, did not leave campus and risk a confrontation with police. In February, a series of marches in <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION> resulted in stone-throwing clashes with police. In an unusual move Tuesday, <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> officials granted permission for the march in their city. The decision coincided with an agreement at negotiations between Solidarity leader <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> and government officials to restore legal status to the student association. Like Solidarity, the student group was banned following the December 1981 martial-law crackdown. The <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> march started when about 1,000 people walked two miles from the <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Polytechnic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> to <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, where they joined about 4,000 students and professors for a rally. Police halted traffic for the march, led by a woman pushing twins in a baby carriage. The marchers chanted `` No success without <ORGANIZATION> NZS </ORGANIZATION>,'' the initials in Polish for the student group. After a wreath-laying ceremony at a campus plaque marking the 1968 events, the participants walked a few blocks off campus to a monument honoring the 19th century Polish epic poet and patriot <PERSON> Adam </PERSON> <PERSON> Mickiewicz </P