<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 1stAdd   03-08 0734</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 1st Add,0773</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: justifiable wrath.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 March 6 The <ORGANIZATION> Seattle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> on drug-treatment rules: Acquired immune deficiency syndrome has broken all the rules, and society is slowly reacting to the epidemic. The latest change is a recommendation from two federal health agencies to make methadone, a synthetic narcotic, more readily available to heroin addicts seeking treatment. The goal is to fight the spread of AIDS through needle sharing by intravenous drug abusers. In less than a decade, this fatal disease has claimed 49,976 lives, and has been diagnosed in 39,000 more people. After a halting start the medical community is in hot pursuit of vaccines, but the disease has proven an elusive target. ... Weaning addicts from needles with methadone or reducing the reuse of needles by distributing clean needles takes a change of attitude for ... professionals, lawmakers and citizens. As the human and financial toll of the AIDS epidemic mounts, society will be reassessing many old values. These early public health adjustments may seem quaint.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 March 3 The Westerly -LRB- <LOCATION> R.I. </LOCATION> -RRB- Sun on equipping new buses with wheelchair lifts: Public transit officials around the country may blanch at the thought of an appeals court ruling that requires equipping new buses with wheelchair lifts for the handicapped. There would be good reason for such a reaction, given the $ 15,000-per-bus cost at a time of dwindling federal subsidies for transit systems. There is even better reason to applaud the court's dictum to the <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. We have a national commitment to ease life for the handicapped insofar as possible. It should be undertaken in spite of the substantial outlay this would entail.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 March 2 The Inter-Mountain, <ORGANIZATION> Elkins </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> W. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, on President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s help for <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>: President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> certainly believes in taking care of his own Among his proposals to improve the nation's productivity are many that directly benefit the state of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. He wants a writeoff for domestic oil. He wants to proceed with the superconducting supercollider, to be located in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. He calls for building a manned space station with headquarters in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. If he has his way, the productivity should be improved in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 March 1 The <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, on acid rain: When asked recently by Canadians when he intended to do something about reducing acid rain clouds that float northward toward the dominion, President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said: `` I have in mind, ` as fast as possible.''' While it's not a firm timetable, it's a welcome change from the stance of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration; it never seemed quite able to figure out where the pollution was coming from. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s move is a good one simply because it is right. There are too many people on the face of our globe to continue abusing it as we have. A commitment from the world's largest industrialized nation to abate this maltreatment comes none too soon. To that end, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has pledged his personal backing, as well as _ to begin with _ $ 2.5 billion over five years for clean-coal technology. Let's hope it produces results.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 March 3 The <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>, on <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s rain forest: Brazilian President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> says he's distressed at the way the world is jumping on <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s case about the destruction of the rain forest. He sits on a high horse and talks about how those in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> have no room to throw stones. It is the industrial nations that gave the world acid rain, a depleted ozone and a growing greenhouse problem, says <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s interior minister. Fine, Mr. <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON>. Do n't listen to those busybodies from countries with economies far healthier than <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s. Listen to <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>. Listen to what <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s diverse, indigenous groups have to say. Several dozen <PERSON> Amazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Indian </PERSON> tribes got together for a conference -LRB- last month -RRB- to demand a say in the development of their homeland. They want dams on a tributary of the <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> stopped. ... These are people who understand how to use the wonderful, mysterious plants of the rain forest. They tap resources the scientists of the developed world have yet to discover. Exchange the wealth of their culture and rain forest for the short-term gain of a dam here or a road there and <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> will shortchange its future. <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> does n't have to listen to world opinion. But for its own sake, it ought to listen to the voices from within.
