<TEXT>
 March 5 The <ORGANIZATION> Rapid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- S.D. -RRB- Journal on Bibles in hotel and motel rooms: In the off-chance that this quest to outlaw <PERSON> Gideon </PERSON> <PERSON> Bibles </PERSON> is n't a joke, let's say that any innkeeper who wants to make the Bible available to guests forces nothing on them, and offers them something of value. Untold millions have drawn comfort, inspiration and insight from the Bible. It's a great book from many perspectives. No one forces a guest to pick up the Bible from the nightstand, any more than the guest is forced to switch on the television. Everyone has the right to seek truth in his or her own way. If the <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> From </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Religion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> is offended by the Bible, its members should n't read it. But trying to deprive others of the opportunity is wrong.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 March 3 Chronicle-Tribune, <PERSON> Marion </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, on killer vegetables: All the recent reports about pesticide-tainted fruits and vegetables have left us a little confused. We're now being told that pesticide residues left on 27 different fruits and vegetables _ such items as apples, carrots, broccoli, grapes and tomatoes _ may eventually cause cancer. If memory serves us correctly, for the past few years we've been told by medical authorities that we ought to eat more of those items to help prevent cancer. Sometimes you just do n't know who to believe.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 March 6 <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Observer, <LOCATION> Raleigh </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, on day care: Day care is a painful dilemma for working parents, whether those parents work to scrape by, or whether they work to afford the status symbols of the up and coming. Finding care for the most important people in their lives, their children, is a financial and emotional burden. It is the burden of government as well, as states seek to define their role in providing day care assistance to those who can not afford it. ... Though it's no longer uncommon for both parents in a home to work full-time, and certainly common for single mothers and fathers to work, employers have taken the attitude that caring for children is the family's problem. It is, but not entirely. Children who are not given adequate care in their first three or four years frequently find themselves behind in school from the start, and they never catch up. That hurts them in the adult work force, and it ultimately hurts their community and their state. In that sense, then, the lack of good day care is everyone's problem
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 March 3 The Register-Guard, <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, on wasting energy: Making more efficient use of energy has always been the key to improving standards of living despite dwindling resources and mounting environmental concerns. But two years ago the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' progress toward more efficient use of energy stalled. Last year, the country actually lost ground in terms of efficiency. ... For the first time since the energy crisis of the 1970s, -LRB- in 1988 -RRB- Americans' appetite for oil, coal, natural gas and other types of energy grew faster than their productive output. A continued decline in energy efficiency would have a number of unwanted consequences. The nation's bill for imported oil _ already $ 40 billion a year _ would rise without a corresponding increase in economic output. The rate at which finite energy resources are depleted would accelerate. Air pollution, acid rain and the greenhouse effect would be aggravated. ... -LRB- M -RRB- any of the problems caused by wasteful energy consumption, ranging from smog to excessive reliance on foreign suppliers, need to be addressed even if energy remains cheap and plentiful.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
