<HEAD>Pope Calls On U.S. Bishops To Support Church's Teachings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with meeting beginning, pope's comments.
No pickup. ^By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> opened an extraordinary meeting with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Roman Catholic leaders today and challenged them to proclaim the church's message in `` a world that does not often readily accept it.'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> spoke briefly in English to 36 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> prelates summoned to <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> for a meeting the Americans hope will ease tensions between <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Catholics and the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>, which has been unhappy about dissent among the American faithful. Many American Catholics, for instance, disregard church teaching on matters such as artificial birth control and remarriage for divorced people. The role of the bishop is expected to be the dominant topic in the 12 hours of discussions with top <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> officials through Saturday. Other issues on the agenda include the family, the sacraments and <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> education. `` I wish to encourage you in your ministry,'' the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> told the bishops, gathered in the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>'s Old Synod Hall. `` I am fully conscious of the challenges you face in bringing the Gospel message to a world that does not often readily accept it.'' `` Your people experience the difficulties of being Christians in today's world. Yet at the same time they search for direction in following the path marked out by <PERSON> Christ </PERSON>.'' Earlier today, a cardinal representing the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bishops declared that <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> democratic freedoms are not at odds with faithfulness to the church. American bishops have maintained that disagreement among Catholics reflects their democratic heritage. The pope, however, says people can not dissent from church teachings and be considered `` good Catholics.'' `` As <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bishops, we valu