o set worldwide trends. The pope summoned much of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> hierarchy to <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> for this week's session: the five active <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cardinals, 30 archbishops and a bishop, all representing major dioceses. <PERSON> Bernardin </PERSON> said Tuesday that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> hierarchy hoped to increase the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>'s understanding of American culture and the church's part in it `` When you are involved in a universal church such as ours, there is a need for communication,'' he said. `` The more we can do, the better everyone understands what is involved.'' May said some problems with <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> stemmed from a `` lack of understanding'' by <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> officials. `` Some of these men have not been in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, or not very much,'' he said in a telephone interview. He said he hoped the meetings lead to a `` deeper understanding of separation of church and state, a deeper understanding of freedom of thought in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> ... a deeper understanding of the democratic process that we're used to, which is not always the way things are done in the church.''
