<HEAD>Space Shuttle Discovery Launch Set For Monday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> unveiled `` 5 Days To Launch'' signs at space center gates Wednesday and said space shuttle Discovery would lift off Monday with five astronauts and a $ 100 million communications satellite. Such signs usually show up about three weeks before a launch but were displayed much later this time because suspect or faulty equipment delayed the launch four times past its target date of Feb. 18. The latest setback came Monday with the failure of a system that commands separation of the two booster rockets and external fuel tank from the spaceship in flight. The problem prevented a Saturday launch. The faulty unit was replaced with one from space shuttle <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday and was successfully tested overnight, <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Malone </PERSON> reported. `` The Kennedy Space Center is pressing on toward a Monday liftoff,'' she said. The countdown for the 28th shuttle launch, and the third since the Challenger accident, was scheduled to start at 12:01 a.m. Friday, with liftoff set for 8:07 a.m. Monday. Discovery's crew, commanded by astronaut <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Coats </PERSON>, was to arrive Friday from the astronaut training base in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. The others are <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Blaha </PERSON>, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Bagian </PERSON>, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Buchli </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Springer </PERSON>. During five days in orbit they will deploy a communications satellite and conduct numerous medical and other scientific experiments.
