t figure up front and his proposal for an increase to $ 4.25 an hour is fair and firm and his last offer.'' Labor Secretary <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said last week that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wants an increase of 90 cents an hour, to $ 4.25, over three years. She said the raise must be accompanied by a provision allowing businesses to pay all newly hired workers $ 3.35 an hour for the first six months of their employment. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s support for some type of sub-minimum was qualified, with the longtime opponent of the provision saying it would have to be accompanied by training and education for new workers. `` The concept of an educational component to the minimum wage, coupled with real training, is not unappealing,'' said <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>. Sen. <PERSON> Orrin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON>, the ranking Republican on the committee and a longtime opponent of the minimum wage, earlier said he will support an increase if Democrats accept a training wage. `` If they'll work with the president, there will be a raise in the minimum wage,'' said <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Utah </LOCATION>. An aide to <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said the senator remains `` nowhere near the administration's position on this'' despite his change. `` We are willing to discuss a training wage,'' said the aide, who spoke on condition of anonymity. `` For the past eight years what we saw was intransigence -LRB- from the White House -RRB-. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration has shown some flexibility and we too are willing to be flexible and to discuss a real training wage,'' said the aide. Other Democrats also said they'll take some form of the `` training wage'' in hopes of reaching agreement with the Republican administration. `` I think some kind of compromise is going to have to be worked out, at some point,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, D-Ill., a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> panel who has also opposed a sub-minimum wage Organized labor has opposed the second tier because of fears that workers would be fired in favor of those covered by the lower standard. But the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> now says it is `` open to discussion on the training wage.'' `` One of the problems in the administration proposal is that every time you take a job you become a trainee again,'' <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Lorrie </PERSON> <PERSON> McHugh </PERSON> said. `` And most of the jobs, the lower-paying jobs are not skill jobs, do n't require training at all.''
