<FIRST>r i AM-Fashion     03-08 0600</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fashion,0617</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ferre, Fendi Dazzle Fashion Crowd</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIELA PETROFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It's a designer's job to make good clothes. Creative genius is another thing. There are lots of nice clothes on the <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION> runway this week where the Italian fall-winter 1989-90 ready to wear collections are showing. But it was n't until the shows of <PERSON> Gianfranco </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferre </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fendi </PERSON> by <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Lagerfeld </PERSON> that the fashion crowd was treated to innovative creations _ the kind experts call works of art and end up in fashion museums. <PERSON> Ferre </PERSON> has always stood out in the <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION> designer crowd, known for its tailored casual clothes, by creating a structured style that looks great on slim, tall models but is more difficult to imagine on the average woman. A broad shouldered sihouette, with cinched waist and narrow hips and either a super short or calf length hemline is his trademark. He loves billowy blouses with big stiff stand-up collars, favors pants over skirts, and likes to nip the waistline in wide belts, and trim cuffs and collars in rich fur. The genius of this winter's collection is the combining of the conventional and the eccentric. Thus a pair of perfectly man-tailored gray flannel pants is spruced up by an intricately pleated black and white blouse, topped by a fox fur scarf, dyed to look like zebra and wrapped around the neck. All of this is wonderful for the fashion pages, but how is one to eat, drink and even talk behind a scarf that covers half the face. <PERSON> Ferre </PERSON> also adorns calf-length beige cashmere tunics with these furry feminine neck warmers. More often than not, the scarves come with warm but equally impractical enormous matching muffs. His blouses not only have have generous collars but also wide cuffs with big gold cufflinks. Along with the staple <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION> shades of brown, black and gray, <PERSON> Ferre </PERSON> uses a lot of red, mixing it with gray flannel by day, and black and gold by night. Adding his voice to the fur debate raised this week between those opting for fake furs and those who wo n't settle for anything but the real thing, <PERSON> Ferre </PERSON> not only interspersed fake and real skins, but dyed real fox to look like fake leopard and zebra. The <ORGANIZATION> Fendis </ORGANIZATION> marched on in their search for unusual, innovative ways to work the pelt. For more than 20 years, the <ORGANIZATION> Fendis </ORGANIZATION> have combined their fur expertise with the designing genius of <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Lagerfeld </PERSON> to create the most imaginative story in the fur market. Several years ago they exhibited their combined technical and creative efforts at <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>'s modern art gallery For next season, <PERSON> Fendi </PERSON> takes the fur to its bare minimum, stripping it of lavish silk and quilted linings and tanning the leather side to look like polished cotton. Thus, every coat is reversible. Sometimes the pelts from the humble beaver to the lofty mink is worked in patches, with tufts of fur pearing through the leather side. At others it is pierced to create a feather-like lacey effect. This minimal look is further emphasized by the taupe-colored ribbed wool tunics and tights that were the exclusive under-coat outfit. There is lots of combining of fur and fabric in this Fendi collection with fur inlays livening up otherwise simple wool coats. These furs _ starting at more than $ 5,000 with some coats at nearly $ 100,000 _ are not for the woman who has saved for years for her one fur coat. The furs are not showy and not terribly warm, and despite the exquisite workmanship, have a fragile look.
</TEXT>
