<FIRST>r w AM-PentagonWaste     03-08 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pentagon Waste,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon Making Scant Progress Against Dangerous Wastes: GAO</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has been largely unsuccessful in developing and implementing a program to minimize hazardous wastes at military bases, the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday. The agency, an investigative arm of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, found that the services have made varying degrees of progress in implementing programs to reduce hazardous waste 50 percent by the end of 1992. `` Clearly the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s efforts to reduce the amount of hazardous waste generated, have to date, been unsatisfactory,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Vic </PERSON> <PERSON> Fazio </PERSON>, D-Calif., one of two congressmen who requested the report The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> study found that the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> report annually on hazardous wastes to the Pentagon but that the report does not require the information be correlated with the workload of major military installations. In addition, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> found a number of inconsistencies and inaccurate methods of data collection, making the information unreliable. `` It's the same old problem we have found in every other aspect of <ORGANIZATION> DOD </ORGANIZATION>'s hazardous waste program _ somehow the message never gets through to the base commander or others responsible for day-to-day waste management activities,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Synar </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Okla </LOCATION>. The Pentagon is spending $ 500 million in fiscal 1989 to clean up the old hazardous waste dumps and other sites and more than $ 100 million a year disposing of newly generated hazardous waste. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> report recommended that the secretary of defense establish a standard methodology for collecting and reporting hazardous waste within the department.
