<HEAD>Dropping Service from Budget Would Cut Deficit $2 Billion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Top managers of the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Postal Service have an idea for lopping at least $ 2 billion off the federal deficit next year _ remove the agency from the budget. `` If we stay ` on budget,' it will increase the general deficit by over $ 2 billion. Taking us off will avoid that,'' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Setrakian </PERSON>, chairman of the agency's governing board, said Wednesday. `` The Postal Service does not belong in the unitary budget,'' agreed Postmaster General <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> at a jount meeting of two subcommittees of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. Much of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> appears to agree, with committee members reporting that they have more than 200 member signatures on a bill to move the agency back out of the federal budget. `` I want to underscore the ... need for ` off-budget''' status, said Rep. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Horton </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N </LOCATION>. The subcommittee chairmen, Reps. <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Leland </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> McCloskey </PERSON>, D-Ind., concurred In pressing for removal from the general federal budget, the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> leaders appealed to the same logic that led to the agency's being included in the overall budget during the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. Once a heavily subsidized <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> department, the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> was made an independent federal agency in 1971. The service's subsidy was phased out and the agency was directed to operate like a business _ breaking even over the long haul and having its own budget Over the years, the agency developed a pattern of operating at a loss some years but making a profit in others _ depending on how recently rates had gone up. But it did break even on average. This was noticed by <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> and in 1985 the post office _ which had a $ 117 million surplus the year before _ was brought back into the federal budget in an effort to make the national deficit appear smaller. The result, however, was that when the government found itself battling a massive deficit last year cuts were imposed on agencies including the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, forcing delays in construction and closing down post offices across the country for a few days. Collecting and sorting mail on Sundays has not yet been resumed because of the budget crunch. The <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> is expected to complete the current fiscal year about $ 600 million in the black, then fall into the red in fiscal 1990 _ adding $ 2 billion or more to the federal deficit if the agency is n't removed from the overall federal budget before then. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> has said he anticipates having to raise postage rates in 1991 to cover that loss, although he commented at the hearing that he would like to stretch out the currrent system of seeking increases every three years. The last rate hike was in 1988.
