<HEAD>Soviet AIDS Cases Rising Fast; Health Minister Says Danger Ignored</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Soviets are expressing alarm over the spread of AIDS at home, with the health minister calling it a threat akin to that posed by nuclear weapons. The number of cases in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is expected to rise almost tenfold next year. As recently as 1987, Soviet officials dismissed AIDS as a largely Western problem due to decadent sexual mores and drug use. <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Gennady </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> called the disease `` a scourge of God for the downfallen morals in our world.'' But now, the daily newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> says, `` The alarming situation with AIDS demands rapid and decisive measures.'' `` A long time ago, some noted epidemiologists reported with certainty that this new 20th century plague would pass us by,'' <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. But the rapidly increasing number of Soviet cases shows `` AIDS is not somewhere ` over there, in their country,' it is among our population,'' the paper said. `` The threat that we face is no less than the ecological ` bomb' or nuclear weapons,'' Health Minister <PERSON> Yevgeny </PERSON> <PERSON> Chazov </PERSON> was quoted by <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> as telling a conference of Soviet epidemiologists convened to discuss the disease In 1988, <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> said, 81 people in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> were carriers of the AIDS virus. By Feb. 1, it said, 44 more cases were known, and now the number of people infected exceeds 140. `` It's expected that next year, there will be 1,342 sick people,'' <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> said, apparently referring to carriers of the virus, rather than people actually suffering the symptoms of AIDS. Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is caused by a virus that damages the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to infections and cancer. It is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products, and from pregnant women to their offspring. <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> said that of four Soviets actually ill from AIDS, three have died. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> reported its first AIDS death in October, a 29-year-old <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> prostitute. <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> quoted <PERSON> Chazov </PERSON> as telling the meeting that the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> ignored warnings that AIDS could become a national calamity. <PERSON> Chazov </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> workers tried many times `` to inform the government that the situation was menacing,'' <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> said. `` But noted scientists dealing with the problem eliminated the acuteness of the question, saying it was all a false alarm.'' In articles that horrified many Soviets, newspapers reported in January that children at a maternity home in <LOCATION> Elitsa </LOCATION>, near the <LOCATION> Caspian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>, had been infected with AIDS because of the multiple use of an unsterile syringe. Nurses at the hospital had been reusing disposable syringes to cover up the sale of unused needles to drug addicts, the reports said. So far, 31 infected children in <LOCATION> Elitsa </LOCATION> have been identified, <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> said, and `` on average, one more is detected every week.'' Just as Soviets are not any more immune to AIDS than Westerners, some are also liable to treat its victims as pariahs, <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> said. `` It seems recently we read about ` AIDS phobia' -LRB- the fear of getting AIDS -RRB- in the <LOCATION> U.S.A. </LOCATION>,'' the paper said. `` We read, and we shuddered: apparently normal, decent people were compelling a sick person to leave town. They were burning down the house where he lived ... We told ourselves then: Well, no, that's impossible here. But things proved that it is possible.'' In the area around <LOCATION> Elitsa </LOCATION>, people throw rocks at cars with license plates from the region `` as if the cars were spreading AIDS,'' Soviet poet <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Kugultinov </PERSON> wrote in <LOCATION> Izvestia </LOCATION> last month. Youngsters from the region are also being discriminated against, he said. `` The relationship of students leaving <LOCATION> Kalmykia </LOCATION> to study in neighboring republics has sharply changed, voices are calling out, demanding to separate them from the dormitories,'' <PERSON> Kugultinov </PERSON> wrote. He said his country should follow the example of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in seeking to prohibit discrimination against AIDS victims. In the past 1 -LCB- years, the Soviets have decreed measures designed to counter the spread of AIDS. In 1987, it became a crime to infect someone else. Regulations announced this year require foreigners who want to stay in the country for more than three months to prove they are free from AIDS. By Western standards, the Soviets, as of now, have only a small problem with AIDS, if the figures published by <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> are accurate. In comparison, the number of AIDS victims in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had risen to 86,157 as of Feb. 16, the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> said.
