<HEAD>FBI Agent Who Crack Brinks Robbery Dies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ADOLPHE V. BERNOTAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Powers </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agent who helped solve the 1950 $ 2.2 million Brinks armored car robbery and was picked for his law enforcement background to manage the first modern American lottery, has died at age 75. Powers died Tuesday in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Myers </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, where he moved in 1978 after retiring as director of the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> lottery. He had undergone bypass surgery in 1979 and last year. The `` Handbook of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Lottery Fundamentals,'' a 400-page reference manual, recognizes Powers as the `` father of <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. lotteries.'' He served as president of several national and international lottery organizations. In his retirement, <PERSON> Powers </PERSON> was a consultant to several state lotteries and companies that produce lottery paraphernalia. Powers, as <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agent in charge of the <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> office, spent six years trying to solve the Brinks case. The break came when one of the hold-up men informed on the others because he felt he did n't get his fair share of the loot. In 1963, after 22 years with the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>, he was hired to manage the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> lottery because its sponsors wanted to prove it could be run without organized crime influence. `` I remember opponents of the sweepstakes saying that the program would create untold law enforcement problems and underworld counterfeiting of tickets,'' he said in an interview shortly after he retired. `` We proved them wrong. We proved a state can operate a lottery with adequate controls and safeguards to protect the public's interest. As <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hampshire </ORGANIZATION> lottery director, Powers, who lived in <LOCATION> Bedford </LOCATION>, was instrumental in lobbying <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to repeal an excise tax on lottery winnings and to allow radio and TV stations to broadcast lottery numbers across state lines. The <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> native graduated from <ORGANIZATION> Lawrence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Appletown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Georgetown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Survivors include his wife, <PERSON> Melva </PERSON>, two daughters and a son. Funeral arrangments were incomplete Wednesday.
