<TEXT>
 A man escaped from <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> in a homemade balloon Wednesday but fell to his death on the western side of the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Wall, police said. An East German passport bearing the photograph of the dead man was found near the site where the balloon crashed, said <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> police spokesman <PERSON> Dieter </PERSON> <PERSON> Piete </PERSON>. He said other documents found in the wreckage indicate a woman also may have been aboard the balloon. Police searched the site for other clues and urged residents to help in the search. <PERSON> Piete </PERSON> said residents in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Zehlendorf </LOCATION> district reported seeing a balloon about 7:50 a.m. floating into the city over the wall. Police found the balloon after it became snared in a tree. <PERSON> Piete </PERSON> said the balloon, made of heavy plastic, had a harness attached to it containing a man's leather jacket. A plastic bag containing a small radio, books and clothing was tied to the harness, he said. After searching nearly eight hours, police found the body of a man several hundred yards from the crash site and the passport of 32-year-old <PERSON> Winfried </PERSON> <PERSON> Freudenberg </PERSON> of <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. `` The picture in the passport matches up with the dead man,'' <PERSON> Piete </PERSON> said. On Sept. 16, 1979, eight people in a homemade hot air balloon floated over East German border fences to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, landing safely near the village of <LOCATION> Naila </LOCATION> in northern <LOCATION> Bavaria </LOCATION>. The story of that escape was later made into a movie. According to official West German figures, 78 people have died trying to escape to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> since <LOCATION> East </LOC