<HEAD>Julia Child's Cake Pan Rhythms Yield Musical Treat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When composer <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoiby </PERSON> watched a videotape of television chef <PERSON> Julia </PERSON> <PERSON> Child </PERSON> whipping up `` a very special, ve-e-ery choc ` late-ly, bittersweet, loooovely cake,'' he knew he had the recipe for a scrumptious musical His 20-minute ode to Miss Child's chocolate cake, with lyrics taken verbatim from the tape of a TV cooking lesson in 1961, had its world premiere Wednesday at the Kennedy Center. The musical monologue, entitled `` Bon Appetit!'' after Miss Child's familiar closing line, featured actress <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Stapleton </PERSON> singing her way around an imaginary kitchen, flouring cake pans and beating egg whites in pantomime to <PERSON> Hoiby </PERSON>'s piano accompaniment. `` Bon Appetit!'' was served up as the dessert course for an evening of <PERSON> Hoiby </PERSON>'s meat-and-potatoes classical fare. Then, at a post-concert reception, the audience was invited to sample the real thing _ <ORGANIZATION> Le </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gateau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> au </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chocolat </ORGANIZATION>, l'Eminence <PERSON> Brune </PERSON> _ prepared from Miss Child's recipe by the <ORGANIZATION> Kennedy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>'s head chef. <PERSON> Hoiby </PERSON> and Miss <PERSON> Stapleton </PERSON> will repeat their musical cake bake, which is scored for small orchestra, during a festival of the composer's music at <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, later this month and at <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.M. </LOCATION>, on April 9. <PERSON> Hoiby </PERSON> confessed that his work on `` Bon Appetit!'' was a severe test of his commitment to a macrobiotic diet, which features such ultra-healthy foods as cabbage, brown rice and fish with seaweed. `` I am tempted not only by the lyrics but by the cake itself,'' he said in a prerehearsal interview. `` I often give in to temptation and say I'll make up for it later,'' he said. `` I love chocolate cake. The things that are out of reach are what we love in this world.'' The 63-year-old composer, who lives and works on a 40-acre farm in the Catskills of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> state </LOCATION>, wrote the piece as a curtain-raiser for performances of a longer, operatic version of the late <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> <PERSON> Draper </PERSON>'s monologue, `` The Italian Lesson,'' which he composed for Miss <PERSON> Stapleton </PERSON> in 1984. <PERSON> Hoiby </PERSON> and associate <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Shulgasser </PERSON> liked the idea of using the script of a Julia Child cooking lesson, and had Miss <PERSON> Stapleton </PERSON> write the TV chef for permission. She happily agreed, sent along a batch of tapes and suggested her recipe for chicken <PERSON> Marengo </PERSON>. But <PERSON> Hoiby </PERSON> thought chocolate cake was a tastier choice. `` She gets pretty carried away about everything, but especially this dessert,'' <PERSON> Hoiby </PERSON> said. During four full days of watching Miss Child's tapes, <PERSON> Hoiby </PERSON> was intrigued by the `` rhapsodic phrases'' and musical metaphors in Miss Child's speech as she banged pots, whisked egg yolks into a yellow ribbon and poured out her creamy chocolate batter with a spatula. `` Her speaking patterns really grab you, the phraseology, the unexpected little interjections,'' <PERSON> Hoiby </PERSON> said. `` There is a kind of musical cadence in her speech which one is n't aware of unless one starts to set it to music, and then there it is.'' Miss <PERSON> Stapleton </PERSON>, a veteran of Broadway musicals who is better known as <PERSON> Archie </PERSON> <PERSON> Bunker </PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON> Edith </PERSON>, on the `` All in the Family'' TV series, agrees. `` What I love is her wonderful sense of theater,'' the actress said of the chef. `` She's not just a cook. She's a character, very rich and very humorous.'' Miss <PERSON> Stapleton </PERSON> makes the most of Miss Child's comic touches, tapping an invisible cake pan and instructing her audience to `` knock out the flour on the floor, if you have a self-cleaning kitchen like mine.'' The music accelerates when she beats egg whites in an unlined copper bowl in a frantic race with an electric mixer. `` We're going to see who wins,'' she sings, `` and I think maybe I'll win ... because I'm bigger.'' Next time _ if there is one _ Miss <PERSON> Stapleton </PERSON> says she'd like to collaborate with <PERSON> Hoiby </PERSON> on the chicken recipe. `` Chickens are always funny,'' she said with a laugh.
