<HEAD>Iran Says Five Soldiers Killed on Cease-fire Line in February</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An Iraqi ambush killed five Iranian soldiers last month despite a cease-fire in the eight-year war between the nations, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> ambassador said Wednesday. Also on Wednesday, a senior Iraqi foreign ministry official, <PERSON> Riyad </PERSON> <PERSON> Al-Kassy </PERSON>, arrived at <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> headquarters for discussions with officials on coming peace talks between the foreign ministers of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. Iranian Ambassador <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Ja'afar </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahallati </PERSON> said he learned of the troop deaths from the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Iran-Iraq </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Observer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, which has monitored the cease-fire since it went into effect Aug. 20. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Undersecretary-General <PERSON> Marrack </PERSON> <PERSON> Goulding </PERSON>, the chief peacekeeper, received reports from his officers that `` five Iranian soldiers had been shot in the back and killed'' Feb. 17, said <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Nadia </PERSON> <PERSON> Younes </PERSON>. `` <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> said that they had been killed in an Iraqi ambush; however, the investigation by -LRB- peacekeeping -RRB- observers could not confirm this,'' she said. <PERSON> Mahallati </PERSON> discussed the deaths in a letter to Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> that said `` Iraqi forces ambushed our patrols'' near <LOCATION> Baneh </LOCATION>, about 20 miles from the border and about 310 miles west of <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>. A communications operator was captured, <PERSON> Mahallati </PERSON> said. Perez de Cuellar reported Feb. 2 that the worst violence on the 740-mile front line occurred Dec. 11 in the southern border region near the <LOCATION> Shatt-al-Arab </LOCATION> waterway dividing <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. Two Iranians were killed in that clash, which involved artillery, rocket and small-arms fire. The armies are separated by only a few dozen yards in many places, and in one spot face each other across 30 yards of desert, <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> said last month. The only previous report of a fatality on the front came just hours after the cease-fire took effect. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON>'s report did not confirm <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s claim that Iraqi gunfire killed a soldier in that case. Peace talks between <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> have been deadlocked since they began Aug. 25. They are to resume in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> in late March or early April with a meeting of Foreign Minister <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Akbar </PERSON> <PERSON> Velayati </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and his Iraqi counterpart, <PERSON> Tariq </PERSON> <PERSON> Aziz </PERSON>. Last week, Iranian foreign ministry officials met with <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> officials to present their views on the talks. <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Saddam </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> proposed Sunday that the nations exchange all 100,000 prisoners of war under the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> Convention, which calls for the repatriation of prisoners after active hostilities cease. The exchange would be separate from the peace talks to allow for progress even if the negotiations remain deadlocked, he said. The talks became deadlocked when <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> demanded that <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> withdraw its troops from 260 square miles of Iranian territory. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> refused and countered that <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> must relinquish its right to search ships in international waters for weapons bound for <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has not searched any ships since the cease-fire took effect.
