<HEAD>Foreign Ministers Conclude Meeting on Eve of Arms Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Foreign ministers of 35 nations ended a three-day meeting Wednesday and stressed that a new round of arms talks should focus on increasing trust as well as reducing weapons. The talks opening Thursday could clear <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> of many of the troops and conventional weapons massed between the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> and the Urals in the four decades since the Cold War. <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> proposed the talks focus first on imbalances and reductions in tanks, artillery and armored personnel carriers. It says the <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> has a 2-1 edge in such weapons. Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> proposed broader talks, saying he wants existing imbalances removed and then a 10 percent to 15 percent cut in troops and all kinds of weaponry, including combat airplanes, over the next two to three years. <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>, which is not a member of either military bloc, on Wednesday backed <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>'s proposal. <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> says it wants to focus first on the tanks and other weapons that could be used in a surprise land attack. <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> on Monday proposed huge cuts in troops and weapons and further talks to strip the continent of battlefield nuclear rockets. But Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> and other Western officials rejected the Soviet suggestion, hinting they viewed it as a ploy t interrupted supply lines, he said. The wage deferral was approved by more than 80 percent of employees, an action that <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> said indicated strong faith in the future of the business. A wage increase scheduled to take effect next fall also will be deferred. The plan calls for the workers to get half of their deferred wages back in December, and the other half is to be returned next February. The Company Store mails about 25 million catalogs annually, employs more than 1,000 workers in its busy season, and had 1988 income of about $ 100 million.
