<HEAD>Opinions Vary on Continuing Import Curbs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The president of the Steelworkers union and a steel executive called Wednesday for extending steel-import restraints, while a group of steel users called the curbs `` the worst possible form of protectionism.'' A debate sponsored by the private <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> brought together advocates and opponents of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s five-year `` voluntary restraint'' program, which was negotiated by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration in 1984 and limits steel imports from 19 countries and the European Community. The import curbs expire Sept. 30. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> pledged just before he was elected to continue the restraints in some form. But opponents of the plan believe they can make a case for ending it, or at least shortening the extension to less than five years and reducing its scope. There was no argument at Wednesday's debate that the annual, product-by-product, country-by-country import ceilings have aided the steel industry's revival. Imports have been reduced to about 20 percent of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market, and employment and profits were up last year over 1987. The issue is whether the restraints are still necessary, and to what degree they have harmed other sectors of the American economy. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, chairman of a coalition of 1,000 manufacturers that rely on steel products, said the curbs have meant higher steel prices and poorer product availability. `` Instead of growth and profitability through competitiveness, our steel industry has a ` circle-the-wagon' strategy of limiting supply through trade protection in order to raise prices,'' said <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Trans-Matic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Holland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich </LOCATION>. But <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>, president of the steel division of <ORGANIZATION> USX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said most of his company's customers accept the need for continued import protection. `` If we lacked customer support, believe me, we would n't be here,'' <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> said. `` Ninety-five percent of our customers are with us.'' The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industry says it lost $ 11.6 billion from 1982 to 1986. The problem, Steelworkers President <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said, is that the conditions that spawned the restraints _ large subsidies by overseas governments to support steel firms _ have not changed. `` Just as we begin to catch up _ and we're a long way _ the worst thing in the world would be to choke off this growth,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> has been investigating the effect of the ceilings on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> steel-consuming industries. Its report later this year is expected to be an important part of the debate over whether the administration should keep the program intact in its present form.
