<HEAD>Teacher Files for Annulment From Soviet Husband</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LYNN, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A teacher who fought nine years to win her fiance's release from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has filed for annulment after nine months of marriage, alleging he used her simply to get into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Condon </PERSON>, a high school language teacher, and <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Novikov </PERSON>, had been reunited on the eve of the 1988 Reagan-Gorbachev superpower summit. <PERSON> Condon </PERSON>, 45, met <PERSON> Novikov </PERSON>, 56, in 1967 while studying in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. She returned to visit him and they made plans to marry, but <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> officials refused to let <PERSON> Novikov </PERSON> leave. In 1979, <PERSON> Condon </PERSON> began lobbying for his release by writing letters and contacting politicians. They were married May 28 in a backyard ceremony to the strains of `` <PERSON> Lara </PERSON>'s Theme'' from the movie `` Dr. Zhivago.'' They exchanged vows in Russian. <PERSON> Condon </PERSON> filed a complaint Feb. 3 in <ORGANIZATION> Essex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Probate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Salem </LOCATION>, alleging <PERSON> Novikov </PERSON> encouraged her love and attention because he wanted to leave the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The complaint also said the marriage was never consummated. <PERSON> Condon </PERSON>, who teaches at <ORGANIZATION> Woburn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, moved <PERSON> Novikov </PERSON> into the four-bedroom home she shares with her mother. <PERSON> Novikov </PERSON>, a chemist, began taking English lessons in an effort to begin practicing his profession. But <PERSON> Novikov </PERSON> moved out Jan. 22 into the home of his wife's brother, according to The Daily Evening Item of <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> The newspaper reported that <PERSON> Condon </PERSON> was upset that <PERSON> Novikov </PERSON> did not contribute to household expenses. <PERSON> Condon </PERSON> has asked the court to declare the marriage annulled, which would return <PERSON> Novikov </PERSON> to his former status as an alien. Federal immigration officials said <PERSON> Novikov </PERSON> could be in trouble if it's found that he entered the country fraudulently. `` He could be deported,'' said <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Whelan </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> deputy director of the <ORGANIZATION> Immigration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. `` It's not that automatic and there's a process to be followed, but that's grounds for deportment. <PERSON> Condon </PERSON> did not immediately return a call to her school Wednesday. No telephone listing was available for her brother's home. When contacted by the Item on Wednesday, <PERSON> Condon </PERSON> said: `` I do n't know why you are calling about this I am late to school. It is snowing outside. I have no comment.''
