<FIRST>r a AM-TempletonPrize     03-08 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Templeton Prize,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>German Scientist And Scottish Minister Share Religion Prize</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A German physicist and a pathbreaking Scottish minister were named as 1989 co-winners Wednesday of the world's most valuable prize, the Templeton Prize for Progress in Religion. The prize this year is $ 435,000. It was the first time the prize has been divided between two winners. A spokesman said judges split in this 17th year of the award. <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedrich </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Weizsaecker </PERSON>, 76, of <LOCATION> Starnberg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION>, was cited for initiating talks between scientists and religious scholars and for research into links between physics, cosmology and theology. The Rev. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> McLeod </PERSON>, 92, of <LOCATION> Edinburgh </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, was named for his founding of the <ORGANIZATION> Iona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>, an ecumenical center of prayer, peacemaking and work. The winners were announced at the Church Center for the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>. The prizes will be presented privately at <LOCATION> Buckingham </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Palace </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> May 10 and publicly in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> on June 10. In statements, <PERSON> McLeod </PERSON> said he would `` use half of the money for direct action against hunger and the other half for work for peace.'' <PERSON> Von </PERSON> <PERSON> Weizsaecker </PERSON> said his share would go to furthering relationships between science and faith. The founder of the prize, American investment counselor <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Templeton </PERSON>, said the international panel of judges picks winners on the basis of their originality in advancing the `` love and understanding of God.'' He said the prize is deliberately kept larger than others, such as the Nobel prizes in science and literature, to indicate that `` progress in religion is more important than progress in any other field.'' `` The accelerating discovery rate in natural sciences needs to be matched by man's spiritual progess and discovery,'' he said. <PERSON> Von </PERSON> <PERSON> Weizaecker </PERSON>, credited for several discoveries in nuclear physics, initiated talks in 1949 at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gottingen </ORGANIZATION> between long-hostile disciplines of science and religion and later at other institutions. <PERSON> McLeod </PERSON>, a Church of <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> clergyman, started the innovative <ORGANIZATION> Iona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> on an island off the west coast of <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> in 1938 and it has since become a much-visited and influential center. For its monastic-type discipline, <PERSON> McLeod </PERSON> set a simple, five-fold rule of daily prayer and Scripture study, tithing, peacemaking and responsible work and service.
