<HEAD>US Criticizes Chinese Use of Force Against Tibetans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> expressed concern Wednesday about the continued violence in <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> and criticized the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> government's use of force against pro-independence demonstrators. `` While we recognize the right of a government to maintain order, we object to the unwarranted use of lethal force,'' said spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON>. After three days of anti-Chinese rioting, official reports have put the death toll in the violence at 12. But Tibetans say far more have been killed, most shot to death by security forces. The unrest, the latest in an 18-month series of demonstrations, has developed into the most serious challenge to Chinese rule in nearly three decades. Thousands of Chinese troops have converged on <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION>, the remote Tibetan city where martial law was declared Tuesday after three days of anti-Chinese rioting. The disturbances began on Sunday, when demonstrators protesting Chinese rule began rioting, stoning police and building bonfires of goods looted from Chinese-owned stores. <PERSON> Redman </PERSON>, asked about the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s reaction, noted that he has spoken on the matter several times recently. He said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government had approached the <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> and its <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nationalities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> about the problem. `` We stressed a concern in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> over human rights in <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>, deplored the violence which has led to many deaths and injuries, and asked for an assessment of developments in <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> and the likely duration of martial law,'' <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said. `` While we recognize the right of a government to maintain order, we object to unwarranted use of lethal force.''
