<HEAD>Western Donors Urge Sudan to Stop War; Canada Threatens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Western donors Wednesday urged the government to end a six-year civil war threatening thousands with starvation, and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> said it will halt economic aid unless the government starts peace talks. Apparently responding to those and internal pressures, Prime Minister <PERSON> Sadek </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahdi </PERSON> on Wednesday sent his interior minister, <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON> <PERSON> Fadil </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahdi </PERSON>, to <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> for talks with the southern rebels. But the move is unlikely to produce results. The <ORGANIZATION> Sudan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> refused to talk to <PERSON> Fadil </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahdi </PERSON> on a recent similar mission because they maintain the government first must endorse a tentative peace agreement reached Nov. 16 Earlier Wednesday, <PERSON> Mahdi </PERSON> told a conference in <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> that his government welcomes a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> call for a month's cease-fire to permit delivery of emergency relief to more than 2 million people facing starvation in rebel - and government-held parts of southern <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> `` The problem is whether we can get the other side to accept this temporary stop for relief efforts,'' <PERSON> Mahdi </PERSON> said. He was speaking at a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> conference of Western donor countries and relief agencies organizing the $ 137.7 million emergency operation. So far $ 45 million has been pledged for food and medication mostly available in <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> operation aims at a massive deployment by air, trains, trucks and <LOCATION> Nile </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> barges to get to 165,000 tons of relief supplies in the south before the rainy season starts in May and isolates the area for at least six months. The rebels, who want the mostly Moslem government to grant political and economic reforms to the predominantly <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> and animist south, have hampered relief efforts by attacking planes and trains escorted by military personnel. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> says 100,000 people could die if the operation fails. Other relief officials say it could be 600,000. Last year, at least 250,000 southerners died, many isolated by the rainy season. Canadian Ambassador <PERSON> Frances </PERSON> <PERSON> Miles </PERSON> <PERSON> Filleul </PERSON> spoke bluntly at the opening of the two-day Conference for Donor Countries and Organizations for Emergency Relief Operations. `` In absence of a settlement and national reconciliation, we will reconsider continuing our other assistance,'' he said, emphasizing <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> would continue humanitarian aid. <PERSON> Filleul </PERSON> criticized the Sudanese government for failing to carry through on a peace proposal negotiated in November between the rebels and the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unionist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, then senior coalition partner in <PERSON> Mahdi </PERSON>'s government. Later, he told reporters <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> would cut its economic aid unless the government took steps toward peace. <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> budgeted $ 56 million for <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> this year, $ 37.5 million of it in emergency humanitarian aid. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> were among other participants that pledged to maintain humanitarian aid to <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>, but did not refer to economic assistance. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> halted economic aid to <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> in January 1988 because the government owed $ 74 million in arrears on military and economic debts, according to <PERSON> Julia </PERSON> <PERSON> Taft </PERSON>, director of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government's foreign disaster assistance program. Humanitarian aid amounting to $ 62 million was maintained between February 1988 and February 1989, she said. `` There will never be an end to the suffering until there is peace,'' <PERSON> Taft </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Mahdi </PERSON> emphatically denied his government was using food as a weapon in the conflict, an accusation also leveled at the rebels. `` We want to dispel this wicked image of the government using food as weapons and being callous to the needs of its civilians'' said <PERSON> Mahdi </PERSON>. In a related development, <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> officials in <LOCATION> Uganda </LOCATION> said a cargo plane failed to arrive Wednesday in <LOCATION> Entebbe </LOCATION>, delaying the start of a major airlift of food to the besieged southern Sudanese town of <LOCATION> Juba </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Matheson </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION> said a C-130 Hercules chartered from the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, apparently was having technical difficulties.
