<HEAD>Producer of Electicity-Using `Worm Gett'r' Complains of Ban Effort</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> businessman complained to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> Wednesday that staff members of the <ORGANIZATION> Consumer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Product </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> had used heavy-handed tactics in trying to ban his only product, a metal worm-harvesting probe that uses electric currents. <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dye </PERSON> of <PERSON> Caldwell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, told the consumer protection subcommittee of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> that agency staff members also had acted in an underhanded fashion in their investigation of his product and had refused to discuss possible safety improvements. His problems, he said, showed that members of the commission should be `` equipped with business knowledge and experience, and most of all, what is lacking now, common sense.'' A safety commission spokesman declined substantive comment, but a commission member defended the agency's effort to get the product off the market, suggesting the device `` probably is against every known product standard in the civilized world.'' <PERSON> Dye </PERSON> and his wife operate P & amp; M Enterprises, producing the `` Worm <PERSON> Gett </PERSON>' r,'' a device to drive worms to the earth's surface. It is made up of two, six or 12 metal prongs inserted into the ground and connected to a common two-wire, 120-volt AC household circuit. The current flowing into the ground forces worms desired by fishermen to rise to the surface. <PERSON> Dye </PERSON> says no one has been killed or injured from the 30,960 probes he had sold at prices ranging up to $ 29.95 since starting the business six years ago, and only one person had been known to receive a shock. However, the commission staff, citing 20 deaths since 1980 from other probes, often home-made, says the `` Worm <PERSON> Gett </PERSON>' r'' instructions are inadequate and the device itself poses a good chance of a shock strong enough to kill. The commission voted in 1987 to seek the recall of the Worm <PERSON> Gett </PERSON>' r. But it failed to win a federal court order in <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> last year to remove the device from the market. An administratve law judge is considering the commission staff's petition to declare the probe a `` substantial product hazard'' that the commission could ban. `` Though a space of 50 years exists, the storm trooper tactics of the SS and the safety Nazi tactics of the staff of the <ORGANIZATION> CPSC </ORGANIZATION> hold many things in common,'' <PERSON> Dye </PERSON> said. `` Attempts were made to compromise with the <ORGANIZATION> CPSC </ORGANIZATION>. Shielding the product's metal probe was suggested by us; instruction changes and warnings were offered. None of these was acceptable,'' <PERSON> Dye </PERSON> said. He said commission investigators by subterfuge got access to his customer lists from his shipping company, and visited customers seeking information. This has caused some customers to cancel orders, he said. His appearance was arranged by Republicans on the subcommittee. Rep. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nielson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Utah </LOCATION>, said, `` This instance of what appears to be an abuse of authority without a sufficient factual basis is of interest because it was one of the prime reasons why the commission was not re-authorized last year.'' The commission and its staff were vigorously defended by <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Pittle </PERSON>, a former commission member who is now technical director of <ORGANIZATION> Consumers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, publisher of Consumer Reports. `` During the nine years I was a commissioner, at least five manufacturers of worm probes ... voluntarily agreed to take the remedial action the commission deemed appropriate,'' <PERSON> Pittle </PERSON> said. `` As an electrical engineer who has spent the last 20 years designing, testing and evaluating consumer products, I continue to believe that selling products that can predictably place live electrodes in the bare hands of consumers is wholly unreasonable _ and probably is against every known product standard in the civilized world.'' `` In my view, the commission and its staff acted correctly in trying to remove this hazard from the market,'' <PERSON> Pittle </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Shiflet </PERSON> said he could not comment in substance because the case was still before an administrative law judge, except to say, `` A settlement offer from Mr. <PERSON> Dye </PERSON> was never sent to the administrative law judge as required by our procedures.''
