<FIRST>r w AM-EconomicOpinions     03-08 0620</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Economic Opinions,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Americans See U.S. Second to Japan in Economic Power, Poll Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Americans by a two-to-one margin believe that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, not the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, is now the leading economic power in the world, according to a public opinion poll released Wednesday. The poll, conducted by <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gallup </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mirror </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, indicated that 59 percent of Americans now rank <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> first with only 29 percent choosing their own country. `` Our survey finds, beneath the surface of general economic contentment, much unease about the loss of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic power to foreign competition,'' said Gallup president <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohut </PERSON>. `` People see our ability to compete as declining in the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> years.'' On the other hand, the survey found that 72 percent of policy makers, executives and other opinion leaders still believe <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is the No. 1 economic power, a sharp difference with the general public. There was just as big a disagreement over the question of foreign investment in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. An overwhelming majority of the public, 70 percent, saw foreign investment in very negative terms, with many fearing that foreigners are `` buying'' <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and threatening national security. But opinion leaders saw foreign investment as a vital source of capital for economic expansion. The survey, one of a series the Los Angeles-based news company has commissioned on <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> attitudes, was conducted between Jan. 27 and Feb. 5. It included one-hour face-to-face interviews with 2,048 members of the general public and had a potential sampling margin of error of plus or minus two percentage points. A separate survey sampled the opinion of 250 government policy makers, corporate executives, Wall Street financiers and foreign investors in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy. The survey of the general public, described as the most extensive ever on economic attitudes, indicated that 54 percent of <LOCATION> Americans </LOCATION> expect things will be better for them financially next year and an additional 28 percent expected no change in their economic outlook. But they were much less optimistic about the nation's overall economic prospects. By sizable margins, the general public said it expected inflation to worsen and interest rates to be rise. Fully 76 percent said they expected taxes to be increased in 1989, despite President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s `` no-new-taxes'' campaign pledge The survey indicated that Americans strongly oppose increasing general income taxes although large majorities were willing to see higher taxes on tobacco, alcohol and on people with incomes over $ 80,000 a year. The poll indicated 85 percent of Americans favored raising taxes on alcoholic beverages to reduce the federal budget deficit, 75 percent favored boosting taxes on tobacco products and 64 percent were in favor of a national lottery to bring in revenues. Four out of five Americans, 82 percent, favored increasing the income taxes of people with incomes above $ 80,000. A smaller majority, 59 percent, endorsed a proposal to create a new 33 percent tax bracket for all income over $ 150,000. While calling the budget deficit a major problem, only 18 percent of Americans could come within $ 50 billion of guessing its size. Last year's deficit totaled $ 155.1 billion, but 28 percent guessed it was over $ 300 billion. Fears of war and international tension were as low as they have been in 40 years, the survey said. For example, 79 percent of the public feels that tensions with the Soviets have been reduced. As a reflection of the eased world tensions, the survey found strong sentiment for cutting the military budget. Asked how to reduce the federal budget by 5 percent, the public opted to take nearly half of the revenues from the defense budget. The public strongly opposed cuts in Social Security or Medicare to balance the budget.
</TEXT>
