stic support of the Japanese scientists because strong endorsement at this level is almost certainly a prerequisite for Japanese participation.'' But the involvement of President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Energy Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> may be ultimately be needed to convince the Japanese to invest in the project, <PERSON> Decker </PERSON> said. Only <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> has committed to helping build the super collider, agreeing to put $ 50 million into the project, a proposed 53-mile underground tunnel south of <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> in which beams of protons would smash into each other with 20 times the energy of today's most powerful accelerators. But neither foreign countries nor <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> will be willing to bankroll the project unless <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> commits to its construction, the panel was told by <PERSON> Decker </PERSON> and <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Luce </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, the state agency handling <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>' role in the project. If <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> goes along with the president and agrees to spend $ 250 million on the project in the fiscal 1990 budget, including $ 160 million for construction, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and foreign countries would read that as adequate commitment to the project, the officials said. The <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is proposing $ 1.8 billion of the total cost come from non-federal sources, including $ 1 billion that <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> has promised to spend.
