<HEAD>Iran Said To Be Building Missile Factory With Help from China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is helping <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> build a factory to make surface-to-surface missiles with a range exceeding 500 miles, Western diplomatic sources said Wednesday. They said construction has gone ahead since a U.N.-mediated cease-fire halted the eight-year Iran-Iraq war on Aug. 20 and that <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> also is continuing to develop its chemical warfare capability. The sources, speaking on the condition of not being identified, said the missile factory is in northeastern <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, but they could give no details. One source remarked: `` It's a missile plant and the Chinese are lending support to build it. That much is known.'' <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> television, monitored in <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s deputy prime minister, <PERSON> Tian </PERSON> <PERSON> Jiyun </PERSON>, ended a five-day trip to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> on Tuesday. It made no mention of weapons, saying only that the visit concentrated on trade and industrial ties. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> both deny any arms deals, but <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and other Western officials say <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has been a main supplier of weapons for <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s regime. They estimated such sales at more than $ 1 billion. Among the arms supplied were two types of jet aircraft and the HY-2 Silkworm and C-801 anti-ship missiles, which have a range of less than 100 miles. The <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> government said a year ago it was building its own version of a `` foreign missile'' _ not further identified _ for use against <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. According to the authoritative reference, <PERSON> Jane </PERSON>'s Weapons Systems, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s arsenal does not include a surface-to-surface missile with a 500 - to 600-mile range, but Western experts said then it would be relatively simple for <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> to have copied Soviet-designed Scud-B rockets acquired from <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> The war between <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, its <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> neighbor, began in September 1980 and was marked by periodic missile bombardments of each other's population centers in what became known as the `` war of the cities.'' <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> capital, lies only 60 miles from the border, and so the initial advantage went to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. Last spring, however, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> began using long-range missiles to hit <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> and other areas of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> previously beyond range. Some analysts have said <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s use of Scud-Bs with boosters to increase their 160-mile range was a major factor in forcing <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> to agree to a truce.
