<DATELINE>SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Mourners wore blue ribbons Wednesday to symbolize commitment to battered women as they laid to rest a woman who police say was bludgeoned to death by her former husband while he was on a prison furlough. `` In a world filled with people who care only for themselves, she was a person who cared deeply for others,'' the Rev. <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> England </PERSON> said of <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bianco </PERSON> during funeral services at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Anthony </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Bianco </PERSON>, 29, a battered wife before divorcing in 1985, last year became a counselor to battered women at an <LOCATION> Elkhart </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> shelter. She rose to program director. `` <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> listened to people who cried out,'' <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> said. `` She healed their wounds. Having experienced pain and hurt herself, she continued to love.'' Nearly 200 mourners, including Ms. <PERSON> Bianco </PERSON>'s two daughters, ages 6 and 10, attended the services and burial at Chapel Hill Memorial Gardens in <LOCATION> Osceola </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Joseph </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Prosecutor <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Barnes </PERSON> said a decision whether to seek the death penalty against Ms. <PERSON> Bianco </PERSON>'s former husband, <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Matheney </PERSON>, 38, would be made next week. <PERSON> Matheney </PERSON> is being held without bail on murder charges. <PERSON> Matheney </PERSON>, who was serving an eight-year prison term for beating Ms. <PERSON> Bianco </PERSON> and criminally confining their children in 1987, was released Saturday from the <ORGANIZATION> Correctional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industrial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Complex </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Pendleton </LOCATION> on an eight-hour pass. Ms. <PERSON> Bianco </PERSON> was beaten to death with the butt of a shotgun Saturday outside her <LOCATION> Mishawaka </LOCATION> home, police said. The force of at least 20 blows to her head shattered the weapon's wooden stock. <PERSON> Matheney </PERSON> was arrested later that day. Ms. <PERSON> Bianco </PERSON> had asked Department of Correction officials to notify her if <PERSON> Matheney </PERSON> was released, friends and family members say. Two prison officers have been suspended without pay for approving the furlough and failing to notify her. Gov. <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bayh </PERSON> immediately suspended the furlough program pending a review. The shelter's Wednesday evening counseling session, which Ms. <PERSON> Bianco </PERSON> was to have attended, was to be held in her honor, said shelter director <PERSON> Michalyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Chilcote </PERSON>. Ms. <PERSON> Bianco </PERSON> had recently joined the <ORGANIZATION> Mishawaka </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on the Status of Women, which will lobby the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> to improve laws to protect victims of domestic violence, said its president, <PERSON> Bonnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON>. Ms. <PERSON> Bianco </PERSON>'s brother, <PERSON> Mark </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Mishawaka </LOCATION>, urged people to wear blue ribbons to symbolize their commitment, as well as his sister's, to helping battered women. Blue was her favorite color, he said. `` Let the people who make the laws know we need changes,'' he said. `` We need more help for battered women's shelters.'' A memorial fund was set up in her name by the women's shelter. In an interview videotaped by prosecutors two years ago, a badly bruised Ms. <PERSON> Bianco </PERSON> said <PERSON> Matheney </PERSON> had threatened to beat her and take the couple's two children. He said `` he would make my life so miserabl