<HEAD>Apartment Building Fire Kills 14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFORT, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fire swept through an old five-story apartment building in this eastern town early Wednesday, killing 14 people and injuring 10, fire officials said. Four people were killed when they jumped from windows after being awakened by the predawn blaze, fire officials said. The 10 others died from burns or asphyxiation by the black smoke that engulfed the corridors. Firefighters, whose ranks swelled to 120, took more than two hours to put out the blaze near the train station in the center of the town 25 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Mulhouse </LOCATION>, near the Swiss border. The building, an old hotel transformed in 1982 into furnished studios, housed students at the <ORGANIZATION> Technological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sevenans </ORGANIZATION> as well as some workers and elderly. The cause of the fire was not immediately known. It was thought to have started in a third-floor stairwell. Defense Minister <PERSON> Jean-Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Chevenement </PERSON>, mayor of the town of 51,000, visited the scene Wednesday afternoon, listening to survivors who told him of the `` disastrous'' state of electrical wiring in the building. Four bodies were found in the ravaged building soon after the fire was extinguished, and the daylong search through the debris turned up six more bodies, according to rescue officials. Ten people were injured, four of them hospitalized, with one person in serious condition, according to the officials. A temporary morgue and medical station were set up in the nearby train station. It was not known how many of the building residents were present at the time of the fire, which fire officials said was <PERSON> Belfort </PERSON>'s worst since 1940
