<SECOND>AM-Mission to Earth,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Experts Support Multi-Billion Dollar Earth Study</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: in last graf, Lennard is correct</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former astronaut <PERSON> Sally </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ride </PERSON> told a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committee Wednesday the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and other nations in the world need to undertake a comprehensive study of the <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> in learn how to protect the planet from the destructive influences of humanity. Ride, the first <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> woman in space, said science now recognizes that activities of civilization `` have begun to affect the conditions of the planet'', but there is little fundamental understanding of how the Earth's weather, geology, oceans and ice react together to influence the environment. `` We do not yet understand how our planet works,'' she said. `` The Earth is a very complicated place. It has to be studied as a system.'' Ride said a project called Mission to Planet Earth would, for the first time, study the Earth in a way that would relate to each other all of the natural and human forces that influence the planet. She was one of three witness testifying in support of the project before the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committee on commerce, science and transportation. Sen. <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>, D-Tenn., a member of the committee, said there is a need for the mission because humans are beginning to realize that industrial chemicals and gases released into the atmosphere have the potential of affecting life on the planet by changing the weather and climate He said most nations already recognize the need to halt release of chemicals that erode the ozone layer of the upper atmosphere, and that carbon dioxide and other gases from industry may be affecting the Earth's climate through the so-called `` greenhouse effect.'' The greenhouse effect is a planetary warming caused by certain gases in the atmosphere that trap heat from the sun. Most of these gases, such as carbon dioxide, are produced mainly by the burning of fossil fuels. Sen. <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hollings </PERSON>, chairman of the committee, said that the costs for the mission have been estimated at $ 20 to $ 30 billion out to the year 2010. Ride said the cost would be about a billion dollars a year, and that foreign nations could pay a share. The former astronaut, who joined the faculty at <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> after leaving <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>, said Mission to Planet Earth would involve nine instrumented satellites, experiments aboard the proposed space station, science stations on <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>, and a data handling system that would analyze all of the collected information. Ride said that the project would require the cooperation and participation of all the Earth's nations. Some nations, she said, could provide at least two of the satellites and most countries could establish and operate ground monitoring stations to gather measurements from all over the globe. Another witness, <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION>, said a coordinated effort between earth, space, ocean and atmospheric studies would be needed to understand how each element affects the weather, climate and rainfall on the planet. He said with a thorough study of Earth from a variety of perspectives would enable scientists within 20 years to make accurate predictions about weather, the changes in geology and climate, and how human actions affect the planet. <PERSON> Lennard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fisk </PERSON>, chief of space sciences at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, said the agency already has made organizational steps toward starting a major effort to study Earth. He said specific plans will be presented to congress in June, including plans for satellites.
