<HEAD>Communist Party Calls for Investigation of Stalinism in Poland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Communist party leaders have ordered an evaluation of Stalinist crimes in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and an analysis of the `` cult'' that surrounded <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s 1950s leader, <PERSON> Boleslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Bierut </PERSON>, the state news agency said Wednesday. The leaders also called for ways to eliminate remnants of Stalinism and urged `` political and moral compensation for actions of lawlessness and wrongs sustained by citizens in the Stalinist era,'' <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> reported without elaborating. <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> said the comments were made at a Tuesday meeting of the Politburo, which `` deemed it necessary to make a comprehensive and in-depth analysis of postulates concerning the activity of <PERSON> Boleslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Bierut </PERSON> and the symbols of his cult.'' <PERSON> Bierut </PERSON>, a slight mustachioed man who was installed as the Polish leader on Soviet dictator <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s orders, directed the Polish <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- communist -RRB- Party from 1948 until his death in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in 1956 after attending the 20th Congress of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bierut </PERSON> became ill at the congress, where <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>, his mentor who died in 1953, was denounced by then-Soviet leader <PERSON> Nikita </PERSON> <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON>. After <PERSON> Bierut </PERSON> died, he was replaced by a populist communist leader, <PERSON> Wladyslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Gomulka </PERSON>, who introduced a political thaw and released thousands of people jailed for alleged political crimes while <PERSON> Bierut </PERSON> was in power. The victims included many members of the underground resistance army that fought the <ORGANIZ