<SECOND>AM-Solar Flare,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>NOAA Scientists Detect Minor Storm from Solar Flare</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A magnetic wave spewed from the sun on Monday during a massive solar flare was detected Wednesday on <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>, but federal experts said it arrived as a `` minor storm'' that should have only small effects on communications. Forecaster <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>, at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atmospheric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Boulder </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>, said instruments detected a proton event, rapidly followed by a geomagnetic storm starting at about 12:30 p.m. EST. He said both events originated from the solar flare that occurred on the eastern edge of the sun on Monday. <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said the radiation and geomagnetism from the flare were small, from the Earth's perspective, because of the angle of emission from the sun `` Had the flare been in the western half of the sun, it could have caused serious problems,'' he said. The sunspot region that spawned the flare, however, is moving farther west as the sun rotates and should be in a position by Monday to pose a greater radiation hazard to Earth if another eruption occurs, said <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>. `` If it blew up on us then, it could be quite exciting,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> NOAA </ORGANIZATION> experts said the sunspot region that produced the large flare continues to be active and that there is a 50 percent chance that another flare will occur before the region rotates out of view over the western limb, or horizon, of the sun. <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said the proton event, which had been forecast for Tuesday, arrived at Earth later than expected because of the eastern location of the flare on the sun. Protons originating from flares are high energy particles that can damage electronics on satellites. <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said the event detected Wednesday was too small to cause such problems. Warnings were sent, however, to power and telephone companies about the geomagnetic storm, he said. He said the storm, though classified as minor, could cause a slight electrical surge on long utility lines at high latitudes. Geomagnetic bursts also can trigger brilliant displays of the aurora, or polar lights, and <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> forecast, `` There should be increased activities at both poles.'' Monday's flare was classified as an X-15, the largest since April 1984. X-rays from the flare were so powerful that they overloaded instruments on <ORGANIZATION> NOAA </ORGANIZATION> satellites that measure solar activity up to a level of X-12. A small flare, classed as an X-1, occurred Tuesday. Solar flares are eruptions that burst suddenly from the face of the sun, sending waves of electromagnetic radiation and charged particles out into space. A burst of X-rays, which crosses the nearly 93 million miles between <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> and the sun in just eight minutes, was detected about 9:05 a.m. EST Monday. It disrupted a <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loran </ORGANIZATION> navigation system and some short wave radio communications, officials said. Goddard Space Center officials said the Solar Max Satellite, monitored by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, also detected the flare on Monday. No problems were reported on any of the 21 satellites monitored by <PERSON> Goddard </PERSON>. The sun goes through phases of intense activity. It passed a low point in 1986 and is now climbing toward an expected peak in intensity later this year or early in 1990.
</TEXT>
