<HEAD>New Orleans Symphony Resumes Concerts After One-Year Layoff</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The New Orleans Symphony, silenced more than a year ago with a nearly $ 4 million debt, set the premiere of its new season Wednesday with a sold-out concert under the baton of conductor <PERSON> Maxim </PERSON> <PERSON> Shostakovich </PERSON>. `` Fanfare For A New Beginning,'' composed by orchestra member <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON>, will launch the program. Also set for the opening were a balloon drop, a party and fireworks. `` I think it's out of danger now,'' said <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, who took over in December as president of the symphony board. `` We have a new emphasis on fund raising and marketing. The symphony has put together a premier organization. `` In a way, the closing of the symphony focused everyone's attention on the problem and made people determined to keep it from happening,'' said <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, who is also president of <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> Coca-Cola Bottling The symphony suspended operations Jan. 16, 1988, almost $ 4 million in debt. The financial crisis had been building for years, blamed on mismanagement before a professional manager was hired in 1986. Despite desperate `` save the symphony'' fund drives, musicians walked out in 1985 and 1987 when they were n't paid, and drastic budget cuts led to dwindling public support. After the 1988 spring season was canceled, a new symphony organization took over. Donations of $ 225,000, earmarked for the symphony if it reopened, will pay off the remaining debts and leave the books in the black Thursday morning, <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said. The symphony's home, the ornate Orpheum Theater, was sold to eliminate $ 2.4 million of the debt. The buyers, whose names have not been made public, have agreed to let the symphony play rent free for the next five years. Lending encouragement to symphony officials was an unexpected surge in public support. Two-thirds of the season tickets for the 12-week spring program have been sold, although officials had considered a one-third sale a mark of success. It is the 53rd season for the symphony and the third as music director for <PERSON> Shostakovich </PERSON>, son of the late Russian composer <PERSON> Dmitri </PERSON> <PERSON> Shostakovich </PERSON>.
