<HEAD>Airline Returns To Roots To Keep Shuttle Afloat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In a bittersweet tribute to the start of the Northeast Shuttle, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday made a desperate attempt to lure passengers back to the service they pioneered in 1961 by offering $ 12 one-way weekend fares and $ 49 one-way weekday fares. `` This is a move to generate revenue right now for <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, vice president for marketing. `` We have to breathe the life of passenger revenues into that operation.'' The fares recall the $ 12 ticket offered in happier times 18 years ago when <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> introduced the original concept in commuter air travel between major cities in the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION>. The current fare is $ 99 one-way on weekdays and from $ 69 to $ 99 one-way on weekends. The company will run full-page newspaper ads, as well as radio spots, in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> this week in hopes of bringing customers home. <ORGANIZATION> Competitor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said it would not slash fares to match, and spokeswoman <PERSON> Pamela </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanlon </PERSON> reacted to <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s play on its old fare: `` We've definitely got a 1989 product.'' She noted that most shuttle passengers are business travelers who are n't sensitive to fare changes. `` It is a businessman's market; it's a must-go market.'' <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> denied the action was aimed at protecting the pending $ 365 million sale of the shuttle service to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> developer <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>. He said <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> wants to at least keep its 62 daily shuttle flights, which normally carry 6,500 to 8,000 passengers, operating during the Machinists strike, which began Saturday and nearly shut down the airline because pilots have honored picket lines. The public's confusion has resulted in some <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> shuttle flights this week with as few as six passengers. `` I can guarantee you we're not making money at $ 12, but I can tell you at no dollars we're making less,'' he said. The newspaper ads invite people to: `` Fly the original shuttle at the original price _ $ 12 one way. We're back.'' Eastern spokesman <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Matell </PERSON> said shuttle passengers are not at risk of being stranded by a bankrupt airline because bankruptcy is still a last resort. Another spokesman, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashlock </PERSON>, said <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> has pulled television ads and canceled other promotions since the strike. Advance bookings are `` near zero,'' said <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON>, executive vice president. Besides its shuttle, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s only other service is a thrice-weekly roundtrip between <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> cities of <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION>. That route requires little promotion even in normal times because of limited competition.
