<FIRST>u i AM-UN-Children'sRights     03-08 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Children's Rights,0569</SECOND>
<HEAD>Convention Leaves Open Rights of Unborn</HEAD>
<UNK>By HANNS NEUERBOURG ^Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday approved a draft convention on the rights of children that leaves open the legal status of the unborn. A <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said the wording of the convention, which is subject to approval by the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, would weaken international laws against employing children in war-related activities. Approval by the 43-nation panel came without a vote after many speakers welcomed the draft but also listed reservations. <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Adam </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopatka </PERSON>, who headed the negotiations on the project since they began in 1978, told the commission it was the `` product of compromises. He cited specifically the draft's definition of a child. Article 1 defines as a child everyone below age 18 unless legal adulthood is attained earlier under national law. Another article has signatories recognizing that `` every child has the inherent right to life.'' The preamble of the draft refers to a 1959 <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> Declaration on the Rights of the Child `` before as well as after birth.'' <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> led the fight for including the preamble. But <PERSON> Lopatka </PERSON> said no consensus was possible on whether to include a reference to the unborn child in the convention's articles. He said negotiators faced `` principal divergence of views on this issue'' and decided to leave it open to national legislation. In daylong debate, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaeger </PERSON> said it was `` the first time that the rights of the unborn child are recognized in an international convention.'' <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Zuomin </PERSON> said his government interpreted the definition of a child as `` not including a fetus before birth.'' Several speakers expressed concern at another key article which commits signatories to `` take all feasible measures to ensure that persons who have not attained the age of 15 do not take a direct part in hostilities.'' <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> were among those criticizing that this offers less protection than existing international norms, including an additional protocol to the Geneva Conventions which says that children under 15 `` must not be allowed'' to take part in hostilities. The observer of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>, speaking last, said the draft's article `` even weakens international humanitarian law and introduces ambiguities.'' The draft's 54 articles include many basic human rights already laid down in other internationally binding accords. Specific provisions commit signatories to protect children against `` all forms of sexual exploitation'' and to prevent `` the abduction, sale of or trafficking in children.'' One article includes a reference to children's right to `` receive and impart information of all kinds ... through any media of the child's choice'' but adds that this right may be `` subject to certain restrictions.'' The West German delegate commented that `` a clarification taking into account parents' rights would have been urgently required because I am sure that no one in this room believes that children should be allowed to watch TV for unlimited hours.'' <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Quentin </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryce </PERSON> said that concern voiced by some parents that the accord may undermine their relationship with their children was unfounded. `` The convention makes abundantly clear the primary responsibility of parents for their children,'' she said. The <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> will have to decide on funds needed for setting up a special committee that is to monitor implementation of the convention.
</TEXT>
