<HEAD>Sandinista Newspaper Claims Contras Mobilizing For Attacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Sandinista newspaper claimed Wednesday that U.S.-backed rebels based in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> are mobilizing for attacks across the border. It cited unidentified sources `` close to the rebel leadership'' in the Honduran capital <LOCATION> Tegucigalpa </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said it had no information other than the report in Barricada, the official newspaper of ruling leftist party. An estimated 11,000 of the rebels known as Contras, the bulk of the U.S.-supported force, are in Honduran camps in the border area with their families. In <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, Foreign Minister <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> <PERSON> Contreras </PERSON> said Wednesday the rebel army should not be disbanded and its fighters repatriated to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> until the Sandinista government fulfills its promise of democratic reforms. That implied a longer period for dismantling the rebel force and greater linkage to reforms in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> than suggested by an agreement the presidents of <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> signed Feb. 14. <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> <PERSON> Contreras </PERSON> urged the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to continue humanitarian aid to the Contras while they remain in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>. `` An armed group devoid of humanitarian assistance and concentrated on our border is a great danger to the security of <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>,'' he told a news conference. The rebels are in the border province of <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paraiso </LOCATION> in camps near <LOCATION> Yamales </LOCATION>, about 280 miles from <LOCATION> Tegucigalpa </LOCATION>. A $ 27 million <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> humanitarian aid package runs out March 31. Some members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> have proposed linking more aid, which President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> says he will request, to the Central American summit agreement. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> halted military aid in February 1988. Central American presidents agreed at the February 13-14 summit in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> to develop a plan for dismantling the Contra force and repatriating its members or relocating them, presumably outside the region. They called for international verification of the accord, which contains provisions for early elections and democratic reforms in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> <PERSON> Busby </PERSON>, special <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> envoy to <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, met with <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> <PERSON> Contreras </PERSON> and President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Azcona </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoyo </PERSON> on Tuesday night and told them the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> wants the Contras to return to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, the foreign minister said. `` Repatriation would benefit the Contras,'' <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> <PERSON> Contreras </PERSON> said. `` It would benefit <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> because it could achieve democracy as the condition for repatration. And <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> would n't have any more armed groups or Nicaraguan refugees in its territory. So everyone wins.'' <PERSON> Barricada </PERSON> said Tuesday the Contras were moving deeper into <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> to avoid detection by international observers, who have not yet been deployed. Contra leaders in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> denied the report. On Wednesday, the paper said 6,000 Contras commanded by former Col. <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Bermudez </PERSON> had moved out of the jungle camps to strategic points on the border. It said they were preparing for `` offensive actions'' against Nicaraguan targets, not demobilization. The Contras have not agreed to the summit demobilization plan. <PERSON> Bermudez </PERSON> said during the summit that some rebels might return to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and continue the war even without <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military aid. The Contras and <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> signed a temporary cease-fire a year ago and comparatively little fighting has been reported since.
