<HEAD>Sullivan Willing To Take Pay Due</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said Wednesday he would `` readily reverse'' his decision to forfeit nearly $ 300,000 in severance pay if <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> determine the money would raise no ethical concerns. A <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committee is looking into the matter with the White House after members expressed concern that <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> was making an undue sacrifice by his decison not to take the payment to avoid any potential conflicts of interest. `` I would readily reverse that decision because, as some of them put it, I'm not a wealthy man,'' <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said in an interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. `` Certainly that's a benefit that's accrued over 13 -LCB- years that I would certainly love to be able to enjoy, especially at this particular time in this town.'' said <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>, whose annual salary dropped from $ 172,000 last year to $ 89,500 in the new job. But <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said he would not reverse his decision until the after the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> completes its review. The severance pay was earned under <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>'s contract with the <ORGANIZATION> Morehouse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, which he founded. Upon his confirmation to the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> Cabinet last week, he stepped down as the school's president and took an unpaid leave of absence as a professor of medicine. He had asked permission to take a paid sabbatical while at <ORGANIZATION> HHS </ORGANIZATION>, but the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> determined the school's policy on paid leave did not meet government ethical standards. The Office of Government Ethics found no ethics problems with the severance payment, but <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> decided to give up the money before the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> position was formalized. <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said his decision was in reaction to news reports at the time that were raising questions about his request for a paid leave. Last week at <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>'s confirmation hearing, members of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> said the sacrifice was unnecessary, unfair and could discourage others from taking government jobs.
