<HEAD>Dubcek Speaks Out Against Treatment of Dissidents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON>, the former Communist leader of <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>, attacked his country's recent jailing of dissidents and said no reform in <LOCATION> Czechoslvakia </LOCATION> is possible unless the events of 1968 are reviewed. As Communist Party chief, <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON> led the liberal reforms known as `` the Prague Spring'' which were crushed by a Soviet-led invasion in August 1968. In an interview broadcast Tuesday night, <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON> was quoted as telling the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> radio: `` It is impossible to start out on a new road unless you have looked at everything behind you. `` This refusal to look the truth about 1968 in the eye is preventing the party and maybe the leadership ... from recognizing that it is not possible to move forward with perestroika -LRB- restructuring of society and the economy -RRB- until you fill in the blank spots of history.'' <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON> was interviewed on Feb. 24 in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>. A transcript of his remarks was made available Wednesday by the <ORGANIZATION> BBC </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. He was also quoted as criticizing the jailing of playwright and human rights activist <PERSON> Vaclav </PERSON> <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> and others after anti-government protests were put down by police in the Czechoslovak capital in January. <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON> called the unrest a `` surface phenomenon'' caused by `` the burden of the last 20 years,'' according to the transcript. <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> was given a nine-month sentence on Feb. 21. Seven other dissidents were tried that week. One was sentenced to a year in prison, one to nine months, and five received suspended sentences and fines. All seven were charged with hooliganism after they tried to lay flowers in memory of <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Palach </PERSON>, a Czechoslovak student who burned himself to death in 1969 to protest the 1968 invasion and the death of reform in his homeland. `` There is a serious issue here and that is that this legal system here does not adhere to the democratic rules of the game or to the democratic rules of law,'' <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON> reportedly said. On Thursday, cultural activists <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jirous </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jiri </PERSON> <PERSON> Tichy </PERSON> face a court in the Moravian town of <LOCATION> Jihlava </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> on charges of anti-state activity that could jail them for up to five years. <PERSON> Milos </PERSON> <PERSON> Jakes </PERSON>, the current <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader, and other prominent members of the Czechoslovak leadership continue to say the 1968 invasion was justified because <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON>'s reforms threatened the socialist system. The refusal to re-evaluate was reiterated in an interview published last month in the Soviet weekly <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> News with <PERSON> Zdenek </PERSON> <PERSON> Horeni </PERSON>, editor of the Czechoslovak party newspaper Rude Pravo. <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> editor <PERSON> Yegor </PERSON> <PERSON> Yakovlev </PERSON> had asked pointedly whether the time had come to re-evaluate the events of 1968. `` Those events are over and done with. We will not return to their reappraisal _ at any rate our generation,'' <PERSON> Horeni </PERSON> replied. `` There is no inner need for this.'' Indications have grown in Soviet news media of some impatience in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> with <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>'s refusal to introduce more reform and with its handling of the unprecedented week of anti-government protests in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> in January.
