<HEAD>Women March For Jobs, Against Sexual Violence</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto ROM2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Women in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> protested sexual violence and demonstrated in favor of abortion and job opportunities to mark International Women's Day on Wednesday. Turkish and <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> women in war-divided <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> were prevented from having their first meeting in 15 years. In <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>, about 4,000 people, mostly students, marched through the historic center with banners urging passage of a sexual violence law approved Tuesday night by the lower house of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>. Other signs demanded the resignation of Health Minister <PERSON> Carlo </PERSON> <PERSON> Donat </PERSON> <PERSON> Cattin </PERSON>, a Christian Democrat who wants a stricter abortion law that would permit fewer abortions. In <LOCATION> Calabria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, students and older women rallied to show their disappointment that the rape and murder of a teen-ager in that southern region last year have yet to yield a conviction. Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, at his weekly general audience at the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>, said he hopes for better appreciation of women in building society and the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>. He noted the `` active presence'' of women in political life around the world. Despite his encouragement of women's participation in the church, the pope has staunchly opposed permitting women to become priests. In September he issued a major document about women that condemned sexual discrimination but upheld the ban on women priests. In <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Turkish </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cypriot </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Rauf </PERSON> <PERSON> Denktash </PERSON> on Wednesday blocked plans for the first meeting since the 1974 Turkish invasion between 60 representatives of <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Turkish </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cypriot </LOCATION> women's organizations The Greek Cypriot women's group said in a statement that the <LOCATION> Turkish </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cypriot </LOCATION> women informed them through the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> force sponsoring the meeting that the <PERSON> Denktash </PERSON> government in the northern Turkish-occupied part of the island refused to allow them to attend. There was no immediate comment from <PERSON> Denktash </PERSON>, who with President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Vassiliou </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cypriot </LOCATION> leader, is engaged in U.N.-sponsored negotiations aimed at reunifying <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>. Despite heavy rain, 2,500 Norwegian women marched in downtown <LOCATION> Oslo </LOCATION> Wednesday night. They carried signs calling for six-hour work days and a minimum annual wage for women of $ 19,500. Activists complained that wage differences between men and women have increased during the 1980s, despite a Norwegian equal rights law. They also defended laws allowing women to choose abortion and lesbians' efforts to come out of the closet, <ORGANIZATION> NTB </ORGANIZATION> said. In <LOCATION> Kristiansand </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>, pro-abortionists were met outside the city cathedral by counter-demonstrators carrying a crucified doll and banners saying: `` Yes to <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON>, No to Abortion.'' In <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>, about 2,000 women marched to the presidential palace Wednesday to denounce President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> for allegedly failing to improve conditions that force thousands of Filipino women to work as maids, strip-tease dancers and prostitutes. `` The poverty and oppression of Filipino women all over the world have only worsened in the three years since <PERSON> Cory </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> was installed in office,'' said a statement distributed by marchers. Many of the marchers, who included farmers' wives, students and urban professionals, carried signs demanding `` Land, homes, jobs and equality for women.'' Some signs said `` No to AIDS, No to <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Bases.'' About 300 helmeted police armed with truncheons stood behind two firetrucks and a row of barbed wire. March 8 was declared Women's Day in 1910 during an <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Women </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Copenhagen </LOCATION> and adopted by the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> in 1975.
