<SECOND>AM-Gregg-Sununu,0693</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gregg Says Sununu Not To Blame For State's Cash Crisis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMA LOVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An unpredictable economy, not the stewardship of former Gov. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> is responsible for <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>'s cash crisis, Gov. <PERSON> Judd </PERSON> <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON> said Wednesday. `` I was left with a very strong state, an extremely positive fiscal situation,'' <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON> commented in response to reports that <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON>, now White House chief of staff, left <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON> with the same financial problems for which <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> denounced <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> during the presidential campaign. <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> forecast a $ 10 million budget surplus in his departing speech to the Legislature in January. Five days later <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON> warned of a potential $ 13 million deficit when he cut most state spending 3 percent. The sudden turnaround prompted Democrats to accuse <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> of masking a deficit to make himself look good and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> bad. The potential deficit was based on revenue projections that are still in debate. Also, the Legislature under-funded several programs last spring when it wrote a supplemental budget for 1989. Legislative leadership said then that better revenue and cost estimates would be available in January to use in adjusting the estimated $ 571 million general fund budget. A supplemental spending bill to ensure the state ends the year in the black is still under consideration. When it appeared agencies were spending more than legislators estimated out of their 1988 budgets, <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> privately twisted arms last spring to produce $ 24 million in lapses, appropriated but unspent funds. That left the state with a $ 13 million surplus last July 1. Usually criticized for being overly cautious in his revenue estimates, <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> says early receipts made him feel confident the state would take in more revenues than estimated by the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> in April. <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON>'s January estimate also was lower than <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON>'s. <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON>'s estimate of how much agencies would return to the treasury on June 30 also was higher than <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON>'s. When <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON> announced the turnaround, he deducted for under-funded programs and used revenue and lapse estimates that were $ 13 million less than those projected by <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON>. <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON> said in an interview last month that <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> `` still could have been optimistic into December'' that his estimates were correct `` and if I were a departing governor, I suspect I would have been.'' A key element in the equation are the lapses. In his six years in office, <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON>'s taskmaster style of management produced the results he sought. In an interview last week, <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> said he felt `` we still would have been able to manage it'' and that based on revenue estimates when he left, a small surplus would have been left even after those bills he felt had to be paid were deducted. Though he warned aggressive management would be required to ensure any of the $ 10 million was left on June 30, <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> did n't mention the debts when he talked about a surplus Critics say that painted too rosy a picture, but <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> says they were n't listening closely. `` For folks to say I did n't say revenues were tight is just not true,'' he says. `` I was the one who said it was going to be a tough, tough biennium.'' <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON> reiterated Wednesday that <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> was n't to blame. `` I do n't point the finger of blame at anyone,'' he said. `` I think we are caught in a situation where revenues are falling. It was an unpredictable situation. I do n't think it was poor management.'' <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON> praised fellow Republican <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>'s Republican-controlled Legislature for prudent use of state funds during <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON>'s three terms as governor `` We had very good stewardship over the last six years,'' he said. <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON> said <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON>'s criticism of <LOCATION> Masschusetts </LOCATION> was justified. While <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> spent supluses on one-time projects, such as the land conservation program, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> spent large sums on new programs that have to be funded or cut in lean times, he said. <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON> predicted the universal health care program enacted by <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> `` is going to bankrupt that state in my opinion.''
</TEXT>
