<HEAD>House Panel Approves Parental Leave Legislation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committee gave party-line approval Wednesday to legislation that would require large employers to provide up to 10 weeks of unpaid leave for parents to take care of newborn or seriously ill children. The bill, a major part of congressional Democrats' domestic agenda, also would require companies with 50 or more employees to grant similar leave to workers who need extended time off to take care of ailing parents. And it would require them to give up to 15 weeks of unpaid leave for the workers' own serious illness. In each instance, the only direct cost to the employer would be to continue whatever company-paid health benefits were in force at the time the worker requested leave. However, many private and public employers, including the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cities </ORGANIZATION>, oppose the measure on grounds it would be overly disruptive to their operations to hold jobs open for workers requesting such extended leaves even though the direct financial cost might be minimal. The measure cleared the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on a 23-12 vote at the end of a daylong meeting in which the panel beat back about two dozen Republican-sponsored amendments. The bill is expected to be scheduled for floor debate in May after facing review by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. Only two major amendments were adopted Wednesday _ one to include congressional offices and another to exempt public elementary and secondary schools from some of the measure's provisions. The amendment applying to public schools was sponsored by Rep. <PERSON> Marge </PERSON> <PERSON> Roukema </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.J. </LOCATION>, who offered it at the urging of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boards </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. She read panel members a letter from the association in which it agreed to drop its opposition to the overall bill if the amendment it sought was adopted. Arguing that whatever was fair for public schools was fair for private schools, Rep. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Bartlett </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Texas </LOCATION>, attempted to amend Ms. <PERSON> Roukema </PERSON>'s amendment to spell that out. He was defeated, 25-10. Later, <PERSON> Bartlett </PERSON> attempted to have the bill spell out that the same special considerations that public schools could apply to teachers on leave _ mainly special leeway in offering them equivalent work, rather than the same work _ would extend to police and fire departments and public health agencies. Again, he was defeated, 25-10.
