<HEAD>Hungary Looks at U.S. Constitution in Drafting Its Own</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The justice minister appealed to <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday for a system of checks and balances to be enshrined in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s new constitution and repeatedly cited the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Constitution as an example. In presenting the main principles of the new constitution, Justice Minister <PERSON> Kalman </PERSON> <PERSON> Kulcsar </PERSON> said the drafters of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Constitution faced many of the same pitfalls <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> confronts today. The constitution, which would mark a significant break from the current 1949 constitution modeled after the Soviet one, is to guarantee civil and human rights and the existence of various parties. Parliament, which began its session Wednesday, also was told by Premier <PERSON> Miklos </PERSON> <PERSON> Nemeth </PERSON> that the government will consider calling a referendum on its highly controversial <LOCATION> Danube </LOCATION> power project. It was the first indication <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> might consider withdrawing from the Gabcikovo-Nagymaros project, which it is building jointly with <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> and with Austrian financial backing. Environmentalists in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> argue that the project will cause irreparable damage to the river. A new law on referendums is due in June. It is part of a package of political reforms designed to complement the new constitution, which is to be adopted by referendum early next year.
