<HEAD>Protests Modify Rail Link To Channel Tunnel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A high-speed rail link from <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to the Channel Tunnel will be built underground and through deep surface cuttings for two-thirds of its way because of environmental protests, <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rail </ORGANIZATION> announced Wednesday. The state network bowed to a furious campaign by residents in southeast <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and picturesque <LOCATION> Kent </LOCATION>, who said demolition along the 68-mile route and the noise of trains would devastate their lives. The changes will increase the cost of the rail link project from $ 2 billion to $ 2.9 billion, <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rail </ORGANIZATION> said. The route wo n't be ready until the late 1990s, so existing railway tracks and lower speeds on the <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> side will have to be used when the Channel Tunnel now being built to link <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> opens in 1993.
