<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and his wife <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> invited six friends to the White House for dinner Wednesday night and then whisked them to the Kennedy Center to see the comedy `` Steel Magnolias.'' It was his first trip to the theater since becoming president and a rare outing from the White House for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who originally had been expected to have an active social life. The Bushes' guests, all longtime friends, were Mr. and Mrs. <PERSON> Fitzgerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Bemiss </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, Mr. and Mrs. <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Ganzi </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and Dr. and Mrs. <PERSON> Tabb </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, also of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The play, written by <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Harling </PERSON>, is a portrait of six Southern women whose lives intersect in a small town beauty shop. It stars <PERSON> June </PERSON> <PERSON> Lockhart </PERSON>, <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Rush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Carole </PERSON> <PERSON> Cook </PERSON>. The story has been made into a movie with <PERSON> Dolly </PERSON> <PERSON> Parton </PERSON>, <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON> <PERSON> MacLaine </PERSON>, <PERSON> Sally </PERSON> <PERSON> Fields </PERSON>, <PERSON> Darryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Hannah </PERSON>, <PERSON> Olympia </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Julia </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>.
