<HEAD>Socialist Mayor's Successor Says He'll Continue Similar Fight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BURLINGTON, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Mayor-elect <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Clavelle </PERSON> promised Wednesday to continue pushing the agenda of retiring socialist Mayor <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON>, though perhaps with a lower voice. <PERSON> Clavelle </PERSON>, the city's director of economic development, won election Tuesday under the banner of <ORGANIZATION> Sanders </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> party </ORGANIZATION>, defeating a Democratic rival by a 53-to-42 percent margin. `` I think what the people of <LOCATION> Burlington </LOCATION> have said yesterday is that we've had Progressive government for the past eight years, and it's been good government,'' <PERSON> Clavelle </PERSON> said at a news conference. While eschewing the socialist label that made <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON> something of a celebrity, <PERSON> Clavelle </PERSON> said in an interview that he favors such leftist goals as workplace democracy and a shift from military to social spending. `` Those who have the money and those who have the power tend to represent themselves pretty well,'' <PERSON> Clavelle </PERSON> said, adding that he sees the job of mayor as being the one who `` tips the scales just a little bit'' toward those without money and power. <PERSON> Clavelle </PERSON> showed surprising strength in traditionally Democratic and Republican wards in his victory over Democrat <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Chioffi </PERSON>. He received 5,626 votes to her 4,400 votes. Two minor party candidates split a few hundred other votes. <PERSON> Clavelle </PERSON>, 39, is the grandson of French-Canadians who came south to work in the woolen mills of neighboring <LOCATION> Winooski </LOCATION>. He said he gets his politics from his working-class background, not from Marxist theory. His term begins April 1. <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON>, 47, who ran unsuccessfully for governor in 1986 and for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last year, announced in December that he would leave politics to teach and write. He does n't rule out another try for elective office. He was first elected mayor in 1981 and won three subsequent two-year terms. He is the only avowed socialist mayor in the nation.
