<HEAD>China Says VD Cases Quadrupling Every Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The number of venereal disease cases in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has quadrupled annually in recent years because of increased prostitution, sexual freedom and contacts with the outside world, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s official news agency said Wednesday. <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said the problem is particularly serious because the sexually transmitted diseases were practically non-existent in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> for decades, and few doctors know how to diagnose or treat them. The report did not give any nationwide figures, but it said <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prevention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> statistics showed an average 312 percent annual growth in VD cases in recent years. It did not say how many years. It said <LOCATION> Canton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s most open city because of its proximity to <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, recorded 10,000 VD cases between 1984 and September last year. The semi-official <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday that a 1-day-old boy in <LOCATION> Canton </LOCATION> recently was found to have been born with gonorrhea contracted from his father. It said he was the ninth child in the city confirmed to be suffering from VD. According to statistics from venereal disease centers in 16 cities, 70.5 percent of sufferers are male. About 77 percent are gonorrhea cases, while 16.77 percent are syphilis. The return of VD was attributed to greater sexual freedom that has broken barriers against premarital sex, more contacts with the outside world and the `` rampancy of prostitution'' in some areas. <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> quoted the daily <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> as saying some women are becoming prostitutes simply to make money, while others are forced into prostitution by gangs and some are frustrated in love and ignorant about sex. Before the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> takeover in 1949, an estimated 10 million people in in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> had VD, 500,000 in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> alone. But the Communist government eradicated prostitution in the early 1950s, and in the early 1960s it claimed that VD no longer existed in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> said that because <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> was VD-free for so long, chapters on the diseases were left out off medical books and doctors are not able to recognize or treat them. Fake medicine dealers and charlatans are exploiting some people afraid to go to hospitals with their problems, it said. In the past few years, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has set up 192 treatment and prevention agencies throughout the country and established a national center in <LOCATION> Nanking </LOCATION>.
