<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHENGDU, China (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Security forces dragged Tibetans from their houses Wednesday as thousands of Chinese troops took up posts around <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION> after three days of anti-Chinese riots, travelers said. By official count, 12 people had been killed and more than 100 wounded in violence since Sunday when Tibetans marched in <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION>, demanding an end to nearly four decades of communist rule and the return of their spiritual leader, the <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON>. Travelers quoted Tibetans as saying the actual death toll was much higher. The <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON>'s government-in-exile in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> offered to hold talks with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> to discuss the future of <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>. The Chinese Embassy in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> refused comment. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> on Thursday accused Tibetan separatists living abroad of smuggling weapons into <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> and instigating riots in <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION>, the Tibetan capital. In a commentary, the official <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> also defended <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s human rights record in <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>, saying it is those opposed to Chinese rule who trample on the rights of the Tibetan people. Foreign witnesses to this week's rioting said they saw no Tibetans with weapons. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> also announced further martial law orders: all foreigners must report to police; Tibetans harboring criminals must turn them in, and <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> will continue to suppress and root out separatists. No reports surfaced of further demonstrations or gunfire on Wednesday and early Thursday, but Westerners in <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION> said troops filled the streets. Beginning at midnight Tuesday, trucks with loudspeakers drove through the city of 70,000 announcing martial law was in effect and ordering Tibetans to stay inside, said foreign travelers, most of whom spoke on condition of anonymity. The foreigners gave the following account: Dozens of trucks packed with soldiers entered the city and troops _ some drinking beer _ set up checkpoints 15 miles outside <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION> and at nearly every block in the city. Soldiers stopped all but official vehicles and arrested Tibetans in the streets. `` They were just collaring people ... and stuffing them into jeeps,'' said an American. Tibetans screamed with fright as Chinese troops pulled them from their homes. `` These were women's voices,'' said an Australian. `` The truck kept coming back. They would pick up a couple people, drive off with a half-dozen militia holding them down, then come back.'' It was not known who the people were, why they were picked up or how widespread the roundups were because the foreigners were confined to their hotels. But foreigners contacted at several hotels said they saw police raiding the homes of ordinary Tibetans along the streets in front of their hotels. Mobs led by Tibetan youths ransacked Chinese shops in three days of rioting through Tuesday, and a European traveler said not one Chinese-owned shop in the old quarter of the city escaped damage. The estimated 150 foreigners in <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION> have been ordered to leave the city by noon Thursday, but they were forbidden Wednesday to leave their hotels to buy tickets. Tourists said they were given a choice of going to <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION> by bus, going to other cities in <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> or flying to <LOCATION> Chengdu </LOCATION>. One traveler said soldiers stopped her and five others from catching a chartered bus for <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION>. Officials later told her they had arranged another bus to the border but wanted $ 4,185, three times the previous price, she said. `` They can shoot people and arrest people, but getting you a ticket and helping you change money is beyond their capacity,'' said one American. The travelers spoke in telephone interviews from <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Chengdu </LOCATION>, the capital of neighboring <LOCATION> Sichuan </LOCATION> province and one of the few points of entry to the remote Himalayan region. Police detained two British reporters overnight. <PERSON> Jasper </PERSON> <PERSON> Becker </PERSON> of the Guardian newspaper said he and a reporter for the <ORGANIZATION> Reuters </ORGANIZATION> news agency were released Wednesday after being questioned, with authorities most concerned about photographs. One Swiss who refused to turn over his film Sunday said police beat him and pointed a gun at his head. He said the police still had his camera and passport and would n't return them until he hands over the film and pays a fine. He said he was not injured. Three Swedes and an American who also took pictures were given back their cameras and passports after they paid fines. The imposition of martial law marked the first time Chinese authorities had taken the step anywhere since the 1966-76 Cultural Revolution. Authorities apparently took the measure to prevent demonstrations on Friday, anniversary of the failed uprising that led the <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON> to flee to <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> in 1959. The violence that began Sunday was the fourth clash in 18 months between <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> security forces and Tibetans. Troops were not deployed in the previous episodes, in which at least 40 Tibetans and police were killed. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> claims <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> has been part of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> since the 13th century. But many Tibetans maintain the territory was an independent nation before the communists took over in 1949. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>, the <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON>'s government-in-exile said it was ready to work for a peaceful solution to the unrest.
