<FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-89 0736EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a w PM-WalterMears Adv09   03-08 0815</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Walter Mears, Adv09,0835</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs March 9 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Panel's Plan Would Streamline Budget-Making</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 That commission hunting for a politically blameless way to deal with budget deficits had to give up the search _ but it did leave some advice on better ways for the government to make spending decisions. That's something <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has been seeking since it went into business, 200 years ago. In a way, the process almost came full circle. The first <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> passed a single appropriations bill and entrusted specific spending decisions to the White House. After all, if you could n't trust <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON>. ... By the 1980s, the appropriations process had become so cumbersome and contentious that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> twice despaired of passing individual money bills and piled everything into a single mammoth resolution, full of detailed orders and restrictions. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> signed under protest, accepting items he opposed in order to get others he wanted, and to keep the government going. He'd vetoed one catchall appropriations resolution during his first term, producing a temporary government shutdown rather than accept spending he said would bust his austerity budget. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> says he will not accept a single, catchall money measure. `` I am going to refuse to sign another omnibus spending bill,'' he said as a candidate. That may be put to the test. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> managed to pass all its money bills on time during the last budget year because of an agreement reached under the pressure of the 1987 stock market crash. With no crisis to enforce discipline, that performance will be difficult to match. While it expired without a bipartisan consensus on deficit reduction measures, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> did agree that any plan to cut deficits will have to include changes in the way government spending decisions are made. `` The balance of power on budget issues has swung too far from the executive and toward the legislative branch,'' the commission's <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> majority said The panel's Democrats did n't go quite that far. After all, these days legislative equals Democrats and executive equals Republicans. Historically, though, the issue has involved the powers of two branches of government rather than competition between the two parties. The commission's 14 members were unanimous on one specific change in the system, suggesting that the government move to two-year budgets instead of enacting a new one each year. They also agreed that budget goals should be drawn more clearly and enforced more stringently. The modern budgeting process dates from 1921, when <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> began requiring presidents to submit detailed annual budgets. That put the executive branch in charge, and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has been whittling at its authority ever since. The current congressional budget system was installed in the name of reform in 1974, setting a series of legislative timetables <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> seldom manages to meet. That law limited the power of presidents to withhold money <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> appropriates, a device that had been used by presidents of both parties, but one that became most bitterly disputed when <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> used it to block increases in more than 100 domestic programs. Presidents have been trying to get around that barrier ever since. Under the law, a president can not withhold appropriated funds unless he advises <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and gets its permission within 45 days. `` At the very least,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said in his first budget message, `` when a president proposes to rescind federal spending, the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> should be required to vote on that proposal instead of killing it by inaction.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also seeks the line item veto, authority for a president to knock a single spending item out of an appropriations bill without rejecting the whole bill. That wo n't happen easily, if at all, because it would undo one of the ways <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> can force a president to accept what it wants done. When an entire appropriation is hostage to an unwanted provision, presidents often sign rather than fight. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had sought the same thing, and the economic commission majority said presidents should have authority either to veto line items or to rescind appropriations once they have become law. Commission Republicans advocated a constitutional amendment to require a balanced budget and, in a bow to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s no-new-taxes pledge, said it should include a ceiling on revenues that can be collected. They also recommended what would amount to a permanent system of appropriations, proposing that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> set up spending resolutions that would continue automatically at the previous year's dollar levels, with no increase for inflation. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is a lot better at setting deadlines than at meeting them, so that might be the most significant change of all were it to happen. It wo n't.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mears </PERSON>, vice president and columnist for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, has reported on <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and national politics for more than 25 years. End Adv PM Thurs March 9
