<FIRST>a a PM-FetalResearchEthics Adv13   03-08 1085</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fetal Research Ethics, Adv 13,1115</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday PMs, March 13, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Tissue from Aborted Fetuses at Center of Scientific, Ethical Debate</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRIGGS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The use of aborted fetuses is redefining the ground rules of medical research, pitting scientists who hope to alleviate suffering against ethicists who fear the specter of Nazi-style experimentation on unwilling subjects. Critics of fetal tissue research envision abortion-for-profit from tissue sales and foresee organ `` parts shops'' in hospitals. Proponents counter that researchers are steering a morally neutral course. Can science separate the use of human material from the way it was obtained? That central ethical question of the <ORGANIZATION> Nuremburg </ORGANIZATION> medical trials following World War II is being raised again over fetal tissue research, a new frontier of medicine. `` The only answer to this obviously is the answer ... which our whole culture is in anguish over: Are these people -LRB- fetuses -RRB- human beings?'' said the Rev. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Neuhaus </PERSON>, a Lutheran theologian who was among more than 500 signers of an interfaith letter urging the federal government to ban funding for research using intentionally aborted fetuses. `` If we learned anything from the medical trials at <LOCATION> Nuremberg </LOCATION>, it is that science is not in itself good. It can be used for good or evil,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Doerflinger </PERSON>, associate director of the Office of Pro-Life Activities of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>. `` Our point is, the way science is implemented has to respect human dignity.'' On the other side there are human concerns, too. For decades, a 52-year-old patient of Dr. <PERSON> Curt </PERSON> <PERSON> Freed </PERSON> has suffered from degenerative Parkinson's disease but now, after implants of fetal tissue to the brain, the man is improving, said Freed of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>. The implants may alleviate the sudden loss of function and other symptoms that <PERSON> Parkinson </PERSON>'s sufferers endure. `` They may find themselves frozen sitting in church, for example,'' Freed said. `` It would be that kind of phenomenon, eliminating freezing episodes.'' A special <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> committee </ORGANIZATION> decided last December it would be `` acceptable'' for the federal government to back medical research involving the transplant of tissue of intentionally aborted fetuses. And a month later, at the annual meeting of the American Association for the Advancement of Science, <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> classified right-to-life advocates who would ban all research with fetal tissues as among `` the enemies of scientific progress.'' Researchers hope that transplanting fetal cells into people with diabetes and <PERSON> Parkinson </PERSON>'s disease may provide an effective treatment, and also see the potential such research has for similarly treating other serious diseases such as Alzheimer's. Tissue can be obtained elsewhere, including from the patient's own body, but some experts say fetal tissue has the advantages of eliminating the need for surgery on the patient to gather the tissue and its immaturity may make it more adaptable `` We must separate the issue of abortion from medical research,'' said the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> NIH </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> committee </ORGANIZATION>, retired federal appeals Judge <PERSON> Arlin </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. The committee recommended guidelines such as prohibiting profits from the sale f fetal tissue, but the panel's majority opinion was that the ethics of where the tissue was obtained largely should not be considered. If not used, fetal brain cells and other tissues would simply be discarded, say many researchers who see no reflection of the moral abyss of the Nazi era. `` From my perspective, the bottom line is, once a woman decides she's going to have an abortion ... I just do n't understand why it -LRB- fetal tissue -RRB- should n't be used,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Myron </PERSON> <PERSON> Genel </PERSON>, a professor of pediatrics and an associate dean of the <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION>. `` I say this as one who had a substantial number of my family destroyed in the Holocaust.'' To others, it's impossible to distance the act of abortion from the use of resulting fetal tissue. `` It's as separate as me being here and you being there and we being held together by only the one bullet which I have just fired,'' said the Rev. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Burtchaell </PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> NIH </ORGANIZATION> panel who dissented from its report. `` It's an absurd claim.'' <PERSON> Burtchaell </PERSON>, a professor of moral theology at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Notre </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dame </ORGANIZATION>, said government sponsorship of fetal tissue research would be the most powerful expression of public approval of abortion since the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s decision in <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON>. The ambivalence and misgivings that make the abortion decision so painful for some women `` could easily be relieved by the rationalization, yes, this is a tragic thing, but some good could come out of it,'' <PERSON> Burtchaell </PERSON> said. If the research becomes profitable, ethical concerns may be forgotten, <PERSON> Neuhaus </PERSON> added. `` Health is big bucks, superbucks, mega bucks. ... There are few things Americans are willing to pay more for than health for the prolongation of life,'' he said. `` The commercial dynamics are powerfully on the side of blocking out moral reflection. It is not in any way far-fetched to envision that in not too many years every hospital will have a parts shop.'' <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Caplan </PERSON>, director of the Center for Biomedical Ethics at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION>, sees a `` vexing moral problem'' with using aborted fetal tissue and believes research must be closely regulated. Fetal tissue should be handled, he said, through a third-party system like that used for organ donations. Such donations are regulated to separate the physicians awaiting the organ from the patient's treatment, in order to assure the patient, as <PERSON> Caplan </PERSON> put it, `` I'm not trying to kill you to get your parts.'' It also is no longer simply academic speculation that someone might create life to destroy it for valuable tissue, <PERSON> Caplan </PERSON> said. `` I know of three people who have been willing to get pregnant to donate tissue either to themselves or a family member.'' Rabbi <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Rudin </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jewish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committe </ORGANIZATION>, who serves on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Task </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> on Life and the Law, finds compelling arguments on both sides. <PERSON> Rudin </PERSON> said he has no objection to the use of fetal tissue for medical research, but he is worried that the practice may encourage abortions and eventually may lead to poor women selling fetal tissue. `` I was raised where science was going to answer all our problems,'' <PERSON> Rudin </PERSON> said. But science per se is neutral, <PERSON> Rudin </PERSON> said. `` Our moral and public policy guidelines are just now catching up with what we're capable of doing.''
</TEXT>
