<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Industrialized nations committed themselves to banning chemicals destroying the ozone layer, but they reacted coolly to Third World demands for money to find substitutes. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and other populous developing nations embarking on mass production of consumer goods containing chlorofluorocarbons reason that since the West invented and produces most of the ozone-destroying chemicals, the West should pay to replace them. Despite the split, the 123 countries at an international conference on the ozone layer agreed Tuesday that pressure is on scientists and industry to find safe alternatives before more damage is done to the fragile atmospheric shield.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The stock market posted a small loss Tuesday after the Dow Jones industrial average made a short-lived run past the 2,300 level. The average fell 4.11 to 2,290.71. The dollar rose against most foreign currencies. Bond prices fell slightly as traders awaited Friday's release of February unemployment figures. A resurgence of commercial and speculative buying pushed platinum futures prices to a 3-month high, boosting gold and silver futures as well; crude-oil futures tumbled; soybeans retreated; grains were mixed; cattle futures advanced; and pork futures fell.
