court papers. The plea agreement forces <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> to dismiss <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> and withhold his more than $ 100 million in 1988 pay and keep at least half of <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>'s pay and fire him if he is indicted. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> said in an accompanying affidavit that the <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> provisions `` were initiated by the government and inserted in the plea agreement at the government's request.'' He said <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> opposed the action but took them `` in order to reach an overall agreement with the government.'' He said <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> would be willing to pay the <ORGANIZATION> Milkens </ORGANIZATION> if not for the pact. Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON> said the government would have no comment on the filings. A hearing on the <ORGANIZATION> Milkens </ORGANIZATION>' motion is set for March 14. One week ago, <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> filed a supporting affidavit for the government in the same case, admitting that <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> `` entered into the plea agreement voluntarily and without coercion after consulting with counsel.'' The government has said the possibility of indictment on more serious charges does not constitute coercion and that <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> was not threatened with RICO charges during negotiations. The <ORGANIZATION> Milkens </ORGANIZATION> are asking <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Kimba </PERSON> <PERSON> Wood </PERSON> to reject or modify the settlement, under which <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> has agreed to pay $ 650 million in fines and restitution and plead guilty to six felonies, because it violates the <ORGANIZATION> Milkens </ORGANIZATION>' rights. To show <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> was under contract with <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>, his attorney Tuesday submitted a 1975 agreement _ still in effect last year _ stating the high-yield `` junk'' bond trader is entitled to a minimum of 15 percent of any profits under $ 1 million to 35 percent of department profits over $ 8 million. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> is one of the biggest targets of a federal securities fraud crackdown and is expected to be indicted on fraud and racketeering charges. He was named in a civil suit filed by the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> against <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> last September but faces no criminal charges and has denied any wrongdoing. The criminal plea can not take effect until the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> settles civil charges with <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>. Negotiations are continuing.
