<HEAD>Critics Say Time Warner Merger Could Reduce Variety on Cable</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The proposed merger of the media giant <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and entertainment producer <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> could lead to fewer programming choices on their huge cable system operations, critics say. Both companies own cable systems that are among the five largest in the nation. The combination would rank second behind the biggest cable operator, <ORGANIZATION> Tele-Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The proposed <ORGANIZATION> Time-Warner </ORGANIZATION> combination could `` diminish the free flow of information,'' said <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwartzman </PERSON>, executive director of <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Access </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Project </ORGANIZATION>, which describes itself as a public interest law firm. He said Tuesday that the combined cable operations may turn to the programming produced by sister businesses at <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> _ which has major movie and television production operations _ rather than buy it from independent producers. `` It will affect the prices paid for programming and the variety and diversity of programming that is available and impair the ability of other companies to come in and compete effectively,'' <PERSON> Schwartzman </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> division that is preparing to launch a new cable network, Consumer News and Business Channel, said the merger could make it tougher to get a big audience for <ORGANIZATION> CNBC </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Rogers </ORGANIZATION> said cable systems with 12.5 million subscribers already have si