of their administrative operations. She said the combination extends a trend toward consolidation in the cable business, which has raised concerns that the operators, who have been freed from federal rate regulation, will boost their prices. Those fears were not borne out last year, the first year of full rate deregulation, when the average basic cable rate rose about 10 percent, down from a 19.7 percent rise the previous year, she said. Time owns 82 percent of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Stamford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn </LOCATION>. It is the second-biggest cable system operator, with about 4 million basic subscribers. <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, has about 1.5 million basic subscribers and ranks fifth among operators. But a combined <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> cable company still would trail Denver-based <ORGANIZATION> TCI </ORGANIZATION>, which has about 9.7 million subscribers. That figure includes its share of subscribers to systems in which it has a part interest, <PERSON> Kagan </PERSON> said. Officials of Time and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> told securities analysts earlier this week that they anticipated no serious antitrust problems with their merger, which was announced Saturday. The merger requires stockholder approval. They said <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> may have to sell <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION>'s cable system in <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, which has 30,000 subscribers, because of <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>'s minority interest in <ORGANIZATION> BHC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which owns television station <ORGANIZATION> KCOP </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> The government prohibits companies from operating a television station and a cable system in the same market.
