<TEXT>
 Forty-two <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> employees got a little extra along with their profit-sharing checks _ a brief chat with the company's vice chairman. <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Poling </PERSON> dropped by <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s sprawling Rouge complex on Tuesday to hand out profit-sharing checks of about $ 2,800 apiece to workers at the <LOCATION> Dearborn </LOCATION> assembly and stamping plants. <PERSON> Poling </PERSON> chatted briefly with <PERSON> Betsy </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> employee for 16 years, who's been at the <LOCATION> Dearborn </LOCATION> assembly plant for 13 of them. `` I told him I was going to put it down on a new car,'' she said after talking with <PERSON> Poling </PERSON>. She said she has n't decided which car she would buy, but it definitely would be a <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>. A little further down the line, <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Hines </PERSON> got his check and told <PERSON> Poling </PERSON> it would go for his daughter's college tuition. <PERSON> Hines </PERSON>, 62, has been a <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> employee for 35 years. And before heading to the line, <PERSON> Poling </PERSON> gave a check to <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> McNulty </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Garden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, who's been working at <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Dearborn </LOCATION> assembly plant for 25 years. `` I already put it in a money market account,'' he said. `` I've always have put it in a money market. <PERSON> Poling </PERSON> said that if a <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> employee had been around to collect all six profit-sharing checks the automaker has issued, the worker would have received about $ 12,200. `` Despite my reputation as a cost-cutter, I'm a strong believer in profit sharing, count on it,'' he said before his stroll by an assembly line on which new <ORGANIZATION> Mustangs </ORGANIZATION> rolled past. More than 152,000 workers received their checks Tuesday. The amount was the second-highest in auto industry history and far outpaced those of <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which will distribute their profit-sharing checks later this month. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> has said its typical worker will receive $ 254, while <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s average check will be about $ 720. Profit-sharing among each of the nation's Big Three automakers is based on financial performance in their North American operations. Profit for those activities must reach certain levels for profit-sharing to kick in. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> began distributing profit-sharing checks in early 1984, and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> has continued every year since. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>, which will mail this year's checks March 14 to about 450,000 hourly and salaried workers, had no profit-sharing payments in 1987 or 1988. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> will distribute its profit-sharing checks Friday to more than 82,000 hourly and salaried workers. The No. 3 automaker did n't begin profit-sharing payments until this year, but handed out $ 500 checks to employees in each of the past two years in lieu of profit sharing Last year, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> provided about $ 3,700 per employee in profit-sharing, the largest in the five-year history of the payments by automakers. The lowest amount <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> workers have received was about $ 400 each in 1984. While some <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> employees celebrated this year's profit-sharing checks with dinners or long-planned purchases, others never will see the money. Last year, in an agreement between <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Wayne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Friend </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, the company withheld profit-sharing checks for more than 2,300 employees who were behind more than $ 500 in child-support payments. For the most part, though, Tuesday was a happy day at <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> factories. `` It makes the whole year worth it,'' said <PERSON> Reginald </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, a quality upgrader at the <LOCATION> Dearborn </LOCATION> assembly plant.
