<HEAD>Soviets Boosting Sales of Nuclear Fuel to American Utilities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Energy Department says growing Soviet sales of nuclear fuel to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> electric utilities are costing the federal government hundreds of millions of dollars in lost business. Energy Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> the Soviets are grabbing customers by offering lower prices, and that erosion of the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s nuclear fuel program by foreign competition posed a threat to national security. `` With excess capacity and a need for hard currency, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has been receptive to opportunities to sell enriched uranium to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> utilities both directly and indirectly through brokers,'' <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> said in a written response to a variety of questions from the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. A text of <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON>' responses was made available Tuesday at the committee's offices. As recently as 1974 the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was the only supplier of enriched uranium to nuclear power plants throughout the non-communist world. Last year the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> share of the world market had plummeted to about 45 percent, <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> said. The Energy Department runs the country's uranium enrichment operations at plants in <LOCATION> Portsmouth </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Paducah </LOCATION>, Ky. These plants increase, or `` enrich,'' uranium-235 atoms beyond their natural concentration for use in nuclear reactors. <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> uranium enrichment operations lost more than $ 170 million in sales over the past three years to the Soviets, who have made about 30 percent of their enrichment capacity available for foreign sales. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> stands to lose another $ 1.7 billion to foreign competition over the next nine years, he said. `` Based on proprietary and government confidential commercial information, the department is concerned that sales of Soviet enrichment services to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> utilitie do in fact pose a very real threat to <PERSON> DOE </PERSON>'s market share,'' <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> wrote. He said the Soviets had succeeded in grabbing new foreign sales of its enrichment services by offering prices as much as 50 percent below the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> price. He said about half the Soviet sales are made to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> utilities through brokerage firms. <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> provided no further details about specific Soviet transactions with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> utilities. <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> said the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration was preparing a legislative proposal to create a government corporation that would take over the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s uranium enrichment operations in order to restore their competitiveness. `` The department does not have the flexibility or discretion to compete effectively in the tight world market which has developed,'' <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> said, adding that maintaining a healthy uranium enrichment business `` has important energy security and national security implications.'' The plants also supply enriched uranium for the government's defense nuclear reactors A 1985 <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> study attributed the loss of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dominance in nuclear fuel sales to concern in foreign countries about the reliability of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> supplies. Many nations also objected to restrictions on nuclear fuel use that were enforced through <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> enrichment contracts, the study said. Rep. <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON>, D-Tenn., introduced a bill last month that would prohibit <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> utilities from directly or indirectly purchasing Soviet enrichment services She expressed concern that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> could become too dependent on the Soviets for nuclear fuel, posing a potential threat to national security. <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> also said the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration is committed to completing a program designed to demonstrate the effectiveness of a new technology for enriching uranium. The technology, called the Advanced Vapor Laser Isotope Separation process, would allow the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to compete with the lower Soviet prices. <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> said the department needed $ 500 million between 1989 and 1991 to complete the demonstration program. He said the process could be put into operation by 1996. The administration has requested $ 148 million for it for the coming budget year.
