he three-year pact. The contract also improved health benefits for families of employees. The union represents about 500 of the paper's 800 union members. The union had compared the pay scale at the <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Examiner </ORGANIZATION>, a money-losing operation for several years, to its sister paper in the <ORGANIZATION> Hearst </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Examiner </ORGANIZATION>. Under the old contract, top-scale <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Examiner </ORGANIZATION> reporters received $ 563 a week, compared to an $ 801 weekly salary paid to <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>'s top reporters. The <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Examiner </ORGANIZATION>'s circulation is 235,000.
