<HEAD>Eastern Want Ad Draws Applicants Despite Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 3rd graf, Never mind, to update number of employees furloughed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 `` Tired of the nine to five grind? See more of the world in a month than most people see in a lifetime,'' the help-wanted ad said. The job? Flight attendant at <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>. Never mind that the nation's seventh-largest airline has furloughed 9,500 employees, grounded almost all of its flights and is teetering on the brink of ruin. Approximately 20 young men and women showed up at a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> hotel on a cold, snowy Tuesday to answer the ad that appeared in Sunday's <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>. The Eastern official who did the interviewing, <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON>, insisted the ad was not placed in anticipation of the strike that hit the airline Saturday. `` What we are doing is trying to fill the commitment we made in the newspaper ads, rather than lock the door. We had no idea we would be faced with this situation,'' <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON> said. Members of Local 533 of the <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, which represents the flight attendants, scoffed at the claim. `` They're hiring scab flight attendants to replace us,'' said <PERSON> Teal </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, a stewardess with Eastern for five years, as she picketed outside the hotel. <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Coughlin </PERSON>, secretary-treasurer of the local, said <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> conducted similar interviews in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> on Sunday and Monday and in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> on Tuesday and planned to do so in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> today. `` We are meeting these people at every hotel,'' Ms. <PERSON> Coughlin </PERSON> said. `` We have had great success in convincing people to turn away. We handed them a flier and told them about other airlines that were hiring flight attendants and would pay them more money, and we said please come back some day when things are better at Eastern.'' The pickets drew the support of Local 25 of the Hotel and Restaurant Employees Union, which represents workers at the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hilton </LOCATION> hotel, where the interviews were held. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON>, executive secretary-treasurer of the local, said he telephoned <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, general manager of the hotel, Monday night and `` asked him to throw Eastern out of there.'' `` His response was that they had already rented the place, and they could n't legally get out of it, but that it was just that one morning, and he did not think they would be back,'' <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON> said. `` It is strange for a union company to hold a meeting of that nature in a union hotel,'' said <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>. `` It was a situation that they could have avoided. I do n't foresee it happening again.'' <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Chatilovicz </PERSON>, labor counsel for the <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hotel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said he spoke with <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s lawyers about the matter Tuesday. The job-seekers, meanwhile, were mostly oblivious to the furor over Eastern. `` I want a job,'' said a young woman who would identify herself only as <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON>. `` I really did n't know about the controversy that was going on.'' She said company interviewers did not talk to her about the union or tell her that people were being laid off. She also said she was not given encouragement that she would get a job. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, an unemployed <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> resident, said he was not aware that Eastern had been struck and was furloughing employ