<HEAD>Biologist To Be Housed For Five Days in Closed Ecosystem</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 2-3 to CORRECT that Earth, not module, is Biosphere
I.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR H. ROTSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ORACLE, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When biologist <PERSON> Abigale </PERSON> <PERSON> Alling </PERSON> steps inside an airlock, she'll begin a stay in what eventually will be a new world on <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>. Starting late today, Ms. <PERSON> Alling </PERSON> is scheduled to live for five days inside a self-contained environment _ a completely closed ecosystem independent of the air, water and nutrients of <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>, which researchers call Biosphere I. Her five-day stay in the module is a precursor to a two-year stay in a larger and more complex version of the airlock, or Biosphere II. Project spokeswoman <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Dyhr </PERSON> said researchers hope Ms. <PERSON> Alling </PERSON>'s five days in the airlock will have no startling developments. In similar but shorter experiments, `` nothing dramatic happened, which is exactly what we wanted,'' she said. `` Nothing unusual goes on, and then that's normal.'' Ms. <PERSON> Alling </PERSON>, a 29-year-old design coordinator for the Biosphere II project, will be monitoring and studying the various systems that control the environment inside the sealed 15,000-cubic-foot glass-and-steel space-frame structure. Project managers on the outside will be doing the same. Ms. <PERSON> Alling </PERSON>'s heart and respiration rate and other vital signs also will be monitored during her five-day stay. `` I will be breathing air that is apart from <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>. Water recycling will be apart from <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>. This is really a milestone,'' Ms. <PERSON> Alling </PERSON> said. The nearly 2.5-acre, 7-million-cubic-foot Biosphere II is under construction, and in September 1990, eight researchers called `` biospherians'' will be sealed inside for two years. The aim will be to see whether man can exist in a complex and evolving but completely enclosed world. Biosphere II will have seven separate environmental systems, including a tropical rain forest, marsh, and desert. About 3,800 plant and animal species are being selected for the project. `` Learning how to do a better job of stewardship of Biosphere I,'' will be the `` big payoff of Biosphere II,'' said <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Hodges </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> and a consultant on Biosphere II. Such global problems as air pollution, acid rain and the greenhouse effect would be some of the issues studied, he said. The $ 30 million Biosphere II project is being undertaken by <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Biospheres </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ventures </ORGANIZATION>, a private company funded largely by <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> oilman <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bass </PERSON>. There have been 2 -LCB- years of unmanned studies and a three-day manned study in the test module.
