is needed before the plan can be sent to creditors for a vote, which is necessary before <ORGANIZATION> Coleco </ORGANIZATION> can emerge from bankruptcy protection. <PERSON> Abram </PERSON>, saying <ORGANIZATION> Coleco </ORGANIZATION> should n't be surprised that most creditors object so strongly to its plan, reminded those in the courtroom of a popular 1960s song called `` Wipe Out.'' `` That's exactly what the unsecured creditors perceive the plan offers them,'' the judge said. `` I ca n't think of another plan where I've seen the unsecured creditors so wholly wiped out as they are in this case.'' Many of those unsecured creditors are investors who own about $ 335 million in <ORGANIZATION> Coleco </ORGANIZATION> bonds. The creditors' committee on Feb. 14 filed a lawsuit against <PERSON> Isaac </PERSON> <PERSON> Perlmutter </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Marden </PERSON>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> financiers who are the only secured <ORGANIZATION> Coleco </ORGANIZATION> creditors, meaning they are first in line for repayment. <ORGANIZATION> Coleco </ORGANIZATION>'s reorganization plan proposes that <PERSON> Perlmutter </PERSON> and <PERSON> Marden </PERSON> be repaid with stock and cash worth $ 70 million of the $ 80 million they are owed, effectively giving them control of <ORGANIZATION> Coleco </ORGANIZATION>. The lawsuit questions business dealings the two had with <ORGANIZATION> Coleco </ORGANIZATION> in the past two years and claims the men owe the company $ 71 million.
