<HEAD>Marble Headquarters Getting Costly Granite Facelift</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT that marble has weakened, but panels
are not loose, according to company. SUBS grafs 6-7 to UPDATE with company
comment about no safety hazard existing, and with details of 1973 panel
falling. Picks up 8th graf, ``We decided ... ''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> did something that <PERSON> Michelangelo </PERSON> did n't, and the oil company could wind up paying some $ 80 million for its artistic blunder. <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> used white Italian marble sheathing on the outside surface of its 80-story headquarters building in downtown <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. But the marble has weakened over the years. So all 43,000 of them will be replaced with granite during a facelift that begins next month. `` Carrara marble, which is what's on the building, is beautiful,'' says <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> architect <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Netsch </PERSON>. `` Michelangelo used it. But <PERSON> Michelangelo </PERSON> did n't leave his work outside.'' The repair job could cost up to $ 80 million before its completion in three years, said <PERSON> Shelby </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>, manager of engineering for <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION>. Stainless steel strapping was installed last year to hold the 350-pound marble panels in place, even though the clips that attach the slabs to the building have never failed, a company spokesman said. In late 1973, a winter storm caused a construction scaffold to hit a slab that fell and demolished a car, said the spokesman <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>. But he said that was before the building opened in 1975, and no pieces have fallen since. `` We decided to bite the bullet rather than continue forever on a maintenance program,'' <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> said Monday of the replacement project. ` We decided to get it over with.'' The replacement granite has a salt-and-pepper look up close, but will be whiter than the marble when viewed from afar, he said. At 1,136 feet, the structure was the fourth tallest in the world when it was completed. It's still the tallest marble-faced building anywhere. The marble was hauled from near <LOCATION> Carrara </LOCATION> in north central <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> at the direction of <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Swearingen </PERSON>, then company chairman, and his socially prominent wife, <PERSON> Bonnie </PERSON>. Now the company says it was a blunder to use the marble, which has badly deteriorated over the past two decades. `` Tests show conclusively that many of the marble panels have lost strength and must utimately be replaced,'' said <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>. The old marble can not be reused in building construction and no decision has been made as to what to do with it once it's removed from the building. It's too weak for buildings and too warped for countertops. Until a buyer is found, the marble will be piled up outside the headquarters, said <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>. The granite comes from a quarry in Mt. Airy, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, which is one of the world's largest suppliers of gravestones. `` This granite is very strong and stable,'' said <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>. `` I wanted to make sure that 15 years from now someone does n't have to go through what I'm going through.''
