<HEAD>Mosbacher Says Private Industry Must Take Lead in High-Definition
TV</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: Top 6 grafs new with testimony; picks up 2nd graf pvs, If
the, removing pvs graf 4, The House, as outdated. ^By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Commerce Secretary <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Mosbacher </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> today that private industry, and not the government, must take the lead in developing high-definition television production in this country. <PERSON> Mosbacher </PERSON> said HDTV sales in this country could reach $ 140 billion in the next 20 years and that the impact of <ORGANIZATION> HDTV </ORGANIZATION> will go far beyond entertainment uses. He cited potential advances in education, retailing and the military and said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> must take a leading role in this developing industry. But the private sector should remain `` pre-eminent'' in this effort, he said, and any <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> funds that are expended for research in HDTV should go to the domestic industry and not to foreign competitors. `` In my view the private sector must take the lead ... and we're the ones who will be getting the hindrances out of the way,'' he said He suggested the government role could include tax incentives and possible antitrust exemptions for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> manufacturers of HDTV products. He said development of a government policy in this regard has the `` highest priority'' at the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and that he expects to be able to make a recommendation to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on the government role in the next two months. A private study released Tuesday said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> must move aggressively into the new high-definition television and flat-screen display industries or lose more than 2 million jobs annually and suffer a $ 225 billion trade deficit in electronics by the year 2010. If the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> does not compete effectively with the Japanese and other nations in the high-technology arena, the personal computer and semiconductor industries alone could have respective deficits of $ 114 billion and $ 76 billion early in the next century, the report from the <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> said. Its author, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>, said: `` Our nation stands at a critical juncture. If we do not create a strong industrial base centered on development of HDTV and flat-display screen technology, it will not only weaken our industrial base, but also reduce the numbers of skilled jobs that are needed to make us more competitive.'' Proponents of HDTV claim it can provide motion picture-quality images on flat television or computer screens using digital components. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> expects to have an HDTV system in full operation by the mid-1990s, whereas the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> telecommunications industry has barely begun testing of HDTV technology. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is soliciting bids for companies to share in a $ 30 million HDTV research and development program. <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said HDTV technology will improve the entire `` food chain'' in the electronics industry. `` HDTVs will be used in the home, as display screens for personal computers, and by the nation's businesses to improve controls over automated production in auto, steel and manufacturing plants, to integrate video and print media in newspapers, and for the collection and transmission of important medical results such as X-rays and computer tomographs,'' <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said. He said he based his study on findings recently released by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. According to the <ORGANIZATION> AEA </ORGANIZATION> study, a `` strong'' scenario represents a case in which 50 percent of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market for <ORGANIZATION> HDTV </ORGANIZATION> is controlled by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies. In a `` weak'' scenario only 10 percent of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market would be controlled by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> concerns. <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said that with a strong HDTV base the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> personal computer industry would attain an estimated $ 176 billion in sales by 2010, in contrast to an expected $ 44 billion in sales with a weak HDTV sector. In the semiconductor industry, sales would be $ 99 billion in a strong <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> HDTV industry compared with $ 25 billion in a weak industry. The trade imbalance in electronics could range from an estimated surplus of $ 10 billion under a strong HDTV program to a $ 227 billion deficit with a weak HDTV program, <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said. In the employment area, the personal computer industry could have 588,000 employees in 2010 under a strong HDTV scenario, or 147,000 employees under a weak HDTV program, he said. In all related industries, including <ORGANIZATION> HDTV </ORGANIZATION> receivers and VCRs, automated manufacturing equipment, personal computers and semiconductors, there could be nearly 1.1 million jobs under a strong scenario and 274,000 jobs under a weak program. <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said spinoff employment from a strong HDTV program could create another 1.1 million jobs _ even more if flat-screen display technology is used extensively in retailing, education or in automobile assembly. The <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> is a labor-backed think tank based in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>.
