<DATELINE>TIFTON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Ray </PERSON>, a witness at the first of 15 hearings on the federal crop insurance program, said the program is wasteful and fails to provide farmers with fair and equitable protection. `` Our country is in tough times right now,'' the congressman said Tuesday. `` We're looking for a decade of economic stagnation. Our debt of $ 2.8 trillion and our interest payments ... have gotten us in such a situation that we must not waste dollars. The bureaucratic way in which the federal crop insurance group was put together causes us to waste a lot of federal dollars. We need to refine that.'' <PERSON> Ray </PERSON>, a Democrat who represents <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>'s largely rural 3rd District, was among 27 witnesses who lined up to testify before the Commission for the Improvement of the Federal Crop Insurance Program. The 25-member commission, created by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to protect more farmers from droughts and other disasters, will hold hearings in 14 states. <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> noted that crop insurance reform has the backing of key <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> lawmakers, including Sens. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> and <PERSON> Wyche </PERSON> <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON>, and said he is optimistic such legislation could win congressional approval. <PERSON> Kellye </PERSON> <PERSON> Eversole </PERSON>, the commission's executive director, said 50 crops, including peanuts, tobacco, soybeans and peaches, are eligible for crop insurance. Growers can select policies that cover 50 percent, 65 percent or 75 percent of their average yields. Ms. <PERSON> Eversole </PERSON> said concern about the nation's record budget deficit could mean farmers will have to rely more heavily on crop insurance, rather than disaster payments. `` We're trying to find out what is wrong with the crop insurance program and why participation is so low,'' she said, noting just 17 percent to 27 percent of the nation's farmers opt for crop coverage. <PERSON> Wilbur </PERSON> <PERSON> Gamble </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peanut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, said the two chief objections of <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>'s 10,500 peanut growers is that crop insurance penalizes growers who have had low yields because of disasters and forces growers to insure all of their crops, rather than acreage that faces the greatest risk. `` The risks in farming are great, and government rules and regulations are constantly changing,'' he said. `` These factors have led to higher costs of production and low prices. We believe it is extremely important to ... help farmers bear the unpredictable risks of farming.'' <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> <PERSON> Deal </PERSON>, a vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Sea </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Island </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Statesboro </LOCATION>, said his bank requires borrowers to have crop insurance on at least some of their crops. `` In many instances we will have insurance only on peanuts or in some cases tobacco,'' he said. `` Only a small percentage of our farmers carry federal crop insurance on corn, wheat, soybeans or cotton. Their reasoning is that the premium is too high for the dollar amount of coverage they receive.'' Another banker, <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Way </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Planters </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Hawkinsville </LOCATION>, said banks may decide to grant fewer agricultural loans unless the crop insurance program is improved.
</TEXT>
