<HEAD>Japanese Spend Record $16.54 Billion On U.S. Property In '88</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Japanese investment in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> real estate rose nearly a third last year with <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> attracting more investment than any other state and <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> more than any other city, a study says. Japanese investors spent a record $ 16.54 billion on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> real estate in 1988, up from $ 12.77 billion in 1977, to boost their holdings to a total of $ 42.88 billion, according to the study by <ORGANIZATION> Kenneth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leventhal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, an accounting firm. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> ranked first among the states with $ 5.62 billion in Japanese investments in 1988, followed by <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> at $ 2.8 billion and <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> at $ 1.87 billion, according to the study, released Tuesday. <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> topped all cities with $ 3.05 billion, with <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> in second at $ 2.8 billion, according to the study. Among the major Japanese investments in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> were the former Wells Fargo office building for $ 147 million, the <ORGANIZATION> Century </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marriott </ORGANIZATION> for $ 85 million and a 49 percent interest in the <ORGANIZATION> Riviera </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Country </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>. The Leventhal figures were more than double the 1988 Japanese investment total of $ 7.1 billion reported last week by <ORGANIZATION> Salomon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATI