<HEAD>Norway's Economic Cure Working Despite Side Effects, Bank Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Norwegian state bank said Wednesday the country's economic health appears to be improving following tough government measures but that rising unemployment is a worse-than-expected side effect. `` There has been signficant progress,'' <ORGANIZATION> Norges </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> said in its quarterly report Wednesday. The central bank praised recent negotiated and legislated wage limits but said unemployment, which doubled in one year to 3.9 percent in February, was higher than expected. Another 2 percent of the jobless were employed in extraordinary government programs. `` There is no simple way to reduce unemployment, but it is vital that the measures used do not undermine efforts to turn the Norwegian economy around,'' said the report. <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Hermod </PERSON> <PERSON> Skaanland </PERSON> said he did not foresee a prompt decline in unemployment but that state intervention will probably not overstimulate domestic demand. Income from <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> oil fields, now pumping 1.44 million barrels per day, plummeted with the 1986 oil price collapse, at the peak of a domestic spending and borrowing spree. Such earlier measures as interest rate hikes and legislated wage limits, now extended to March 31, 1990, helped turn <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>'s trade deficit into a January surplus of 3.7 billion kroner, or $ 552 million, and reduce 1988 consumer spending by 1.6 percent.
</TEXT>
