<SECOND>AM-Auto Supply, Bjt,0706</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rising Car Inventories And Strong Production, Can They Mix?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> automakers are likely to relay more on sales incentives than on production cuts to reduce swollen inventories of unsold cars, analysts say. <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> have been maintaining production levels that have led to a big rise in the number of automobiles on hand. The authoritative <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>'s Automotive Reports said that at the end of January, there was an 85-day supply of of cars made by U.S.-based companies in inventory, up from 67 days at the end of December. Although incentives tend to cut into the automakers' profits, they are more appealing to customers and autoworkers, who want to keep production high. `` It's becoming increasingly clear that if you can maintain production volumes at a fairly steady pace, it's easier to control raw materials, your work force is happy and, ultimately, your warranty costs come down,'' said analyst <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirnan </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Kidder </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peabody </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` I think they're going to hesitate on the -LRB- cutting -RRB- production route as long as possible and rely heavily on incentives,'' <PERSON> Kirnan </PERSON> said Wednesday. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s inventory was reported at 95 days, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s at 80 days and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s was at 89 days, the weekly journal said. Higher inventories early in the year are n't particularly worrisome to automakers, since January and February sales typically are slower than other months and companies sometimes build up their supplies before the usual spring sales rush. However, there is some concern on Wall Street. `` To the extent that inventory stays up and sales go down, something has to give,'' said analyst <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> Verschell </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> `` Eventually, there will have to be an adjustment, cut production or increase incentive programs.'' <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> has done both. Earlier this week, the nation's No. 1 automaker extended some existing incentives into April and May and created new ones in an effort to lure buyers to dealers' showrooms. Last week, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> doubled a two-week shutdown of its <LOCATION> Doraville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Oldsmobile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cutlass </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> assembly plant because, as plant manager <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> said, `` We've got too many cars out in the field.'' <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> did not immediately match <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s new incentives, but its existing enticements have no time limits. On the same day <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> issued its new incentives, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> Vice Chairman <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Poling </PERSON> said his company would remain competitive with other car makers' marketing schemes. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> is in better shape. For months, the No. 2 automaker has been producing more than 15 percent of its vehicles on overtime, meaning <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> can withstand a sales slump and still remain at full production. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>, meantime, has been struggling in sales as a number of its factories change over to new models or begin `` ramping up'' production of newly introduced cars. Last week, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> Vice Chairman <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenwald </PERSON> said the Big Three would be tested this month, when sales are expected to rise from January and February levels amid continued reliance on incentives. Car sales by the Big Three are down 10.6 percent during the first two months of this year compared with January and February of 1988. February car sales for <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> were 14.4 percent below the pace for the same month last year. Verschell and <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Heaney </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Nikko </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> wondered whether the usual spring buying surge would be enough to shrink inventories to levels easing pressure to boost incentives or cut production `` There are just so many cars out there fighting for the same consumer,'' <PERSON> Verschell </PERSON> said. `` I do n't think it's going to be enough to reduce it,'' <PERSON> Heaney </PERSON> said. But <PERSON> Kirnan </PERSON> was more bullish about spring sales, saying, `` The inventory problem will probably disappear by late March and early April, and production schedules are probably going to be maintained for the second and third quarter. `` I just do n't the,'' <PERSON> Kirnan </PERSON> added. `` I think thee degree that some people believe,'' <PERSON> Kirnan </PERSON> added. `` I think the traditional types of incentives are going to continue to do some magic.''
