<HEAD>Dollar Up; Gold Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar strengthened Wednesday against all major currencies in moderate trading as some traders concluded that the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration was showing flexibility on a tax increase to reduce the federal budget deficit. Gold prices declined after rising overseas. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> quoted a bid of $ 391.90 a troy ounce of gold around 4 p.m. EST, down $ 1 from Tuesday's late bid. Currency dealers attributed the dollar's rally Wednesday to a report quoting <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Boskin </PERSON>, chairman of President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisers </ORGANIZATION>, as saying the administration `` has not ruled out a discussion'' of taxes as part of a formal budget negotiation. <PERSON> Boskin </PERSON> also said the administration has not abandoned its opposition to higher taxes. His statements were consistent with those of other administration officials in recent weeks. Nevertheless, the market chose to interpret <PERSON> Boskin </PERSON>'s testimony as good news for the dollar. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>, senior currency trader for <ORGANIZATION> Irving </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is now conceding that he may allow higher taxes.'' Dealers said there were reports of the Federal Reserve selling small amounts of dollars to stem its rise Wednesday but that most market participants saw that intervention as more symbolic. `` I think they just wanted to remind us that they were still out there,'' <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> said. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar fell 0.30 Japanese yen to a closing 128.73 yen. It also was quoted at 128.73 yen in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, and later, in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, it rose to 129.225 yen from 128.825 yen Tuesday. The dollar gained against the British pound in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, where it cost $ 1.7200 to buy one pound, cheaper than $ 1.7220 late Tuesday. Sterling fetched $ 1.7155 in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, down from $ 1.72155. Other later dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with Tuesday's rates, included: 1.86325 West German marks, up from 1.85525; 1.5910 Swiss francs, up from 1.5845; 1.20145 Canadian dollars, up from 1.19825; 6.3230 French francs, up from 6.3030; and 1,366.875 Italian lire, up from 1,362.625 Late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with late Tuesday: 1.8585 West German marks, up from 1.8520; 1.5865 Swiss francs, up from 1.5847; 6.3080 French francs, up from 6.3000; 2.0930 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0945; 1,362.20 Italian lire, down from 1,362.37; and, 1.20155 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1985. On the Commodity Exchange in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, gold bullion for current delivery closed at $ 393.10 a troy ounce, down from $ 393.30 late Tuesday. Gold rose in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a late bid price of $ 393.80 an ounce, compared with $ 391.45 bid late Tuesday. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, gold closed at a bid of $ 394.75 an ounce, vs. $ 390.90 Tuesday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold rose $ 4.74 to close at a bid of $ 388.21 an ounce. Silver prices also were mixed. On <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Comex, silver bullion for current delivery settled at $ 5.865 a troy ounce, down from $ 5.874. Silver rose in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a late bid price of $ 5.91 an ounce from $ 5.88 Tuesday.
