<HEAD>Shareholders File Suits Against Time-Warner Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Shareholders filed three suits in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> state court Wednesday to block the planned $ 18 billion merger between <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. One of the suits, filed by four <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> shareholders against <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>'s board of directors and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> Chairman, <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON>, alleged the merger and a planned preliminary exchange of stock between the two companies _ known as a lock-up transaction _ would prevent an outsider from making a possibly higher bid for <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> In the lock-up, <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> will exchange 12.5 percent of its stock for 12 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>'s shares. Such transactions commonly are undertaken by companies planning to merge as a defense against unwanted takeovers. `` The merger and lock-up transaction are nothing more than a plan and scheme by the director-defendants to entrench themselves and to make it much more difficult and highly unlikely that <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> will be subject to an outside takeover,'' said the class action suit, filed in <ORGANIZATION> Delaware </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chancery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. The suit asked the court to declare the merger void or alternatively prevent the defendants from proceeding with it. The merger, which would be accomplished through a stock swap, would create the world's largest communications concern, <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. Spokesmen for Time and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> said their companies had no comment on the suit. Court papers for the other two suits were not immediately available, and it was not immediately known who filed the actions or who the defendants were. The suits were filed in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> because Time and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> are incorporated here.
