<SECOND>AM-Apples-Schools,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Apples Pulled from Big Apple School Menus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If a student in the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> wants to give teacher a little apple, it will have to come from home. Fresh apples have been pulled from school cafeteria menus because of worries about carcinogenic pesticides. <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION>, which feeds students in 1,200 public and parochial schools under a federal program, barred the sale of apples last month, at least until it receives advice from the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Gill </PERSON>, director of support services for the board. The Washington-based <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resource </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> has reported that the pesticide diaminozide, which is known by its brand name Alar, could increase the incidence of cancer in children who drink a lot of apple juice. Apple growers contended only about 4 percent of all apples sold in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> show any traces of Alar and those amounts are well below <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> standards. Alar is used to maintain firmness and resist bruising in fruits and vegetables. <PERSON> Gill </PERSON>'s program sells or hands out about 13 million apples a year. He said students had not been complaining about the fruit's disappearance `` It's only been a few weeks, and we offer a wide variety of fruits,'' he said. Applesauce and apple juice are harder to replace and will continue to be served, he said.
