 A <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> investor group that has agreed to buy <ORGANIZATION> Worlds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wonder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> announced Wednesday it plans to appoint the former president of <ORGANIZATION> Mattel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> as president and chief executive. The group named <PERSON> Joshua </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Denham </PERSON>, who served as president of <ORGANIZATION> Mattel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> from 1979 to 1983 and most recently was president of Wonder Products in <LOCATION> Bosler </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Denham </PERSON> will assume responsibility for operating the company after confirmation of a bankruptcy reorganization plan. Worlds of Wonder, which at one time had $ 300 million in annual sales with toys like <PERSON> Teddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruxpin </PERSON> and Lazer Tag, filed for Chapter 11 protection in December 1987. The investor group agreed Feb. 20 to purchase Worlds of Wonder for an undisclosed amount. The group is led by <PERSON> Eli </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobs </PERSON> and includes <PERSON> Franklyn </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, former president of <ORGANIZATION> Fisher-Price </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Toys </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Edelman </PERSON>, former president of <ORGANIZATION> Ingram </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Software </ORGANIZATION>. The acquisition still must be approved by the federal bankruptcy court. The group expects confirmation of its reorganization plan in mid-May, according to a Worlds of Wonder statement. Following confirmation of the reorganization plan, the current president and chief executive officer of the company, <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON>, will return to the <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> management consulting firm <ORGANIZATION> Nightingale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the statement said.
