<HEAD>Milken Scheduled To Give First Speech Since Drexel Plea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Multimillionaire financier <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> is planning his first speech here since <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> agreed to fire him as part of a securities fraud plea deal with the government, his spokesman said Wednesday. <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> is scheduled to deliver the keynote address next week at a financial industry black-tie dinner honoring the `` chief executive officers of the decade'' as selected by Financial World magazine, spokesman <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Lerer </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> was named in a <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> civil suit against <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> last September in connection with securities fraud charges that included insider trading. He is expected to be indicted on criminal fraud and racketeering charges. <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> has headed <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, `` junk'' bond financing department since the mid-1970s and is credited with turning the low-cost, high-yield securities into a $ 175 billion annual market. The bonds often are used to finance takeovers and the growth of small - to medium-sized companies <PERSON> Lerer </PERSON> said <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> last spoke in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> at a business luncheon in December, several weeks before terms of <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>'s plea deal with the government settling criminal charges against were announced. Under the deal, <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> agreed to pay $ 650 million in fines and restitution and plead guilty to six felonies. The deal is pending a separate settlement with the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> on civil charges. <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>, who has denied any wrongdoing, recently asked a federal judge in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> to modify or throw out the agreement on the grounds it violates his rights. <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> agreed in the deal to dismiss <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> and withhold his 1988 compensation of well over $ 100 million. <PERSON> Lerer </PERSON> said <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> is working part-time at <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> while preparing his legal defense. He said <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> also regularly attends charity and financial community dinners. He is not scheduled to receive an award at the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> dinner.
