<HEAD>Help Wanted Ad Volume Declines in January</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The volume of help wanted advertising declined in January, indicating the demand for labor continues to fluctuate, the <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday. The business-supported financial research organization said its Help Wanted Index declined to 155 in January, compared with readings of 161 in December and 157 in November. In January 1988, the index, which measures the volume of classified advertising in 51 major newspapers across the country and is considered sensitive to changes in demand for labor, stood at 152. The <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said the volume of help wanted ads rose in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> regions during January. Volume declined in all other parts of the country.
