<HEAD>Soybeans Tumble As Speculators' Nerve Crumbles</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 13th graf, West Texas ..., to CORRECT that crude oil prices
rose, sted fell.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Soybean futures prices fell as much as 10 -RCB- cents a bushel Wednesday, erasing much of the past week's gains as speculators unnerved by the looming Brazilian harvest and an increase in farmer selling backed away from the market. On other markets Wednesday, energy futures posted strong gains on signs of renewed tensions between <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>; precious metals retreated; copper futures fell; and livestock and meat futures finished mostly lower. Grain futures followed soybeans lower on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>. Wheat settled 1 -RCB- cents to 4 cents lower with March at $ 4.30 a bushel; corn was -RCB- cent to 2 -RCB- cents lower with March at $ 2.75 -LCB- a bushel; oats were 2 -LCB- cents to 5 cents lower with March at $ 2.05 a bushel; soybeans were 5 cents to 10 -RCB- cents lower with March at $ 7.55 -LCB- a bushel. Soybean growers in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, the world's second-largest producer after the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, are preparing to harvest their largest crop ever. The movement of Brazilian _ and then Argentine _ soybeans into the global pipeline will help ease the supply tightness that has contributed to the market's recent firm tone. The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has estimated <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s 1988-89 soybean crop at 20 million metric tons compared with 17.8 million the previous year. On Wednesday, a widely watched private weather service raised its Brazilian soybean estimate to 20.7 million metric tons from 19.6 million. `` I think the real question is not whether it's going to be a record crop, but how much of a record,'' said <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Mao </PERSON>, a grain specialist with <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> soybean growers harvested 1.54 billion bushels last year, or about 41 million metric tons. <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> said said a rise in soybean prices over the past 10 days had prompted more selling of stockpiled beans by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> producers. Oil futures rallied on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> following a report that <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> ambassador had accused Iraqi soldiers of killing five Iranian soldiers on Feb. 17. The incident would mark the bloodiest clash between the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> nations since the beginning of their 7-month cease-fire. The energy market's rally also was seen as partly a reaction to Tuesday's weekly <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> report, which showed declines in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> stocks of gasoline and distillates, although crude-oil supplies increased. West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 24 cents to 45 cents higher with April at $ 18.54 a barrel; heating oil was .29 cent to .97 cent higher with April at 51.37 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .44 cent to .83 cent higher with April at 51.85 cents a gallon. Gold and silver futures retreated on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, selling off late in the session after gold for April delivery encountered resistance at $ 398.80 a troy ounce. <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Savaiko </PERSON>, a metals analyst with <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said April gold's failure to close above $ 396 an ounce indicated `` the recent rally is tiring.'' Gold settled 30 cents to 60 cents lower with April at $ 395.40 an ounce; silver was 1.2 cents to 1.8 cents lower with May at $ 5.947 a troy ounce. Copper futures also finished lower on the Commodity Exchange after initially rising. Analysts said the decline reflected perceptions that physical demand for copper has slowed with the metal's rise in price during the past month. Copper settled 2.9 cents to 4.1 cents lower with May at $ 1.404 a pound. Weakening cash markets contributed to a late slump in cattle futures on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Most pork futures retreated on ideas that Wednesday's increase in hog marketings would result in lower cash prices on Thursday. Live cattle finished .25 cent to .45 cent lower with April at 77.12 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .40 cent lower to .03 cent higher with March at 81.65 cents a pound; live hogs were .20 cent lower to .08 cent higher with April at 44.10 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .25 cent lower to .12 cent higher with March at 38.85 cents a pound.
