<HEAD>Oil Prices for Far East Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prices for Mexican crude oil exports to the Far East rose by 23 cents per barrel in February over January levels, the government oil monopoly <ORGANIZATION> Pemex </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday. Exports of <ORGANIZATION> Pemex </ORGANIZATION>'s light Isthmus crude sold in the Far East at $ 15.08 a barrel last month, up from $ 14.85 in January, <ORGANIZATION> Pemex </ORGANIZATION> said. The monopoly's heavy Maya grade sold at $ 12.43 a barrel in February, up from $ 12.20, <ORGANIZATION> Pemex </ORGANIZATION> said. `` These price increases for Mexican export crudes reflect the favorable evolution of the international petroleum market,'' <ORGANIZATION> Pemex </ORGANIZATION> said. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> has announced it will cut its exports April 1 by 5 percent, or 68,600 barrels a day, to buttress producers' efforts to shore up prices on the international market. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s base level of exports was 1.35 million barrels per day in 1988. The <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> agreed last year to cut its members' production by 4 million barrels a day, to around 18.5 million barrels. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, the world's sixth-largest oil producer, does not belong to the 13-nation cartel but closely monitors its pricing and production guidelines. Most Mexican crude exports to the Far East market are purchased by <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s third-biggest customer last year, <ORGANIZATION> Pemex </ORGANIZATION> said. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> will buy 180,000 barrels per day of Mexican crude in 1989.
